<FIRST>r i AM-Argentina     06-05 0426</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Argentina,0441</SECOND>
<HEAD>Head of Peronist Party Says Alfonsin Should Step Down Early</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By OSCAR J. SERRAT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BUENOS AIRES, Argentina (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The head of President-elect
Carlos Menem's opposition Peronist Party said Monday that President
Raul Alfonsin should step down before his term ends in December so
Menem can take office early.
   Party president Antonio Cafiero said it was for the good of the
country. Argentina is besieged by economic crisis, political
paralysis and social unrest. Inflation topped 70 percent in May.
Interest rates remain at near record highs. Business is contracting.
   Cafiero said ``the country can't wait until Dec. 10'' for Menem,
winner of May 14 national elections, to assume the presidency.
   Food stores were looted in major Argentine cities last week, and
14 people were killed. The national and provincial governments
expanded programs of public subsidies to ease the situation.
   Aides to Alfonsin and Menem discussed an early transition, but
failed to agree on policies to stabilize the economy. Alfonsin
favors increased tariffs to balance the budget. Menem opposes any
program that would further shrink purchasing power.
   Menem also has insisted that Peronists who won congressional
seats on May 14 take office when he does. With those seats, his
party has working majorities in both houses.
   Menem's public position has been that the decision to shorten
Alfonsin's six-year term ``does not depend on me, but on the
outgoing government.''
   But Cafiero said Menem's decision to announce his Cabinet
appointees ahead of schedule last weekend was an indication that
``he (Menem) feels the conviction that this situation cannot be
prolonged.''
   Seven of eight ministers were named on a bipartisan list that
the financial daily Ambito Financiero called ``almost impeccable.''
   Ricardo Lopez Murphy, a key adviser to Menem's presidential
opponent, Eduardo Angeloz of the governing Radical Civic Union, was
offered the post of Central Bank president. Italo Luder, the
Peronists' presidential candidate in 1983, was named defense
minister.
   Cafiero said on Radio Provincia de Buenos Aires, ``The legal
procedures exist for the anticipated delivery of power.''
   ``I think it might happen between August and October. The dates
Aug. 17 and Oct. 12 should not be discarded.''
   Aug. 17 is the anniversary of the death of Gen. Jose de San
Martin, Argentina's founder. Oct. 12 is the date traditionally used
in Argentina to transfer power from one government to another.
   Last week, the country's biggest labor union, the most
influential business group and a major political party suggested
that Alfonsin step down early. Former President Arturo Frondizi
said he thought Alfonsin should resign immediately.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
