<FIRST>u a AM-DomesticPartners     06-05 0546</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Domestic Partners,0559</SECOND>
<HEAD>San Francisco Mayor Signs Domestic Partners Bill</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVE WILSTEIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   San Francisco became the first city in the
country Monday to grant official public recognition to homosexual
and unmarried heterosexual couples.
   Mayor Art Agnos signed the landmark law, calling it ``one of the
most important milestones in San Francisco's effort to adopt
policies to recognize the diversity of families and to extend to
all people in our city the basic human right to form families of
their choice.''
   The law ``has created a framework that clarifies the serious
nature of family relationships in the lesbian and gay community and
for other couples in committed relationships,'' Agnos said.
   Agnos also appointed a ``Task Force on Family Policy'' to
determine guidelines for allowing unmarried city workers to add
partners, adult children and extended family members to the city's
health plan.
   Though denounced by leaders of the city's powerful Roman
Catholic Church as an attack on marriage and the traditional
family, the new law won the unanimous support of the Board of
Supervisors before going to Agnos for his signature.
   ``This is important legislation because it's a step in helping
our country come to terms with the lives of parts of the American
family that have not always been dealt with, particularly lesbian
and gay couples and particularly in the time of an AIDS epidemic,''
said Harry Britt, president of the Board of Supervisors and author
of the bill.
   Agnos said it would take about two months to set up the
mechanisms and distribute the information to allow unmarried
parters to declare their relationship, either publicly through a
county clerk for $35 or confidentially with a notary public.
   He said the city attorney and the city Human Rights Commission
are developing an informational package that will outline the
rights and responsibilities of the relationships.
   Registering under the law affirms the current city policy of
providing city workers in non-traditional relationships with the
same hospital visitation rights and bereavement and maternity leave
as married city employees.
   To qualify for registration, a city worker must live with and
share basic living expenses with their partner. Registration is
intended only for people who live or work in San Francisco.
   Agnos dismissed worries that the law was an invitation to gay
couples or unmarried heterosexual couples from around the country
to go to San Francisco to legitimize their relationships.
   ``It's an invitation for gays and lesbians and all single people
in this country and in the world to take a lesson from the San
Francisco model once again and take to their own communities the
modern kind of family practices that are outlined here,'' he said.
   Matt Coles, an attorney who drafted the law and previously
helped draft similar laws in other California cities, said San
Francisco's measure differs significantly from those in Berkeley,
Santa Cruz and West Hollywood.
   Those cities, he said, pay health benefits to city workers with
domestic partners.
   ``That's important and that's what the task force is aiming at
here,'' he said. ``But what this legislation does is it recognizes
the existence of non-marital relationships. And it recognizes them
whether you're a city employee or not. ... Nobody in the world has
ever done anything like that before.''
</TEXT>
