<FILEID>AP-NR-06-05-89 1018EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Palme     06-05 0528</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Palme,0547</SECOND>
<HEAD>Defendent With Criminal Past Tried in Palme Murder</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ARTHUR MAX</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>STOCKHOLM, Sweden (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man who went on trial today for the
1986 murder of Olof Palme denied that he gunned down the prime
minister.
   ``I did not kill Prime Minister Olof Palme. I did not try to
kill Mrs. Palme,'' defendant Carl Gustaf Christer Pettersson told
the court. ``The shooting was an infamous crime that I could never
have committed.''
   Palme was shot in the back from a distance of eight inches on
Feb. 28, 1986 as he walked home from a movie. The gunman escaped
down a dark side street.
   Mrs. Palme was slightly wounded by a second bullet, and
Pettersson also faces charges of attempted murder.
   Chief Magistrate Michael af Geijerstam called the trial to order
in Stockholm District Court. He broke a five-month news blackout on
the defendant's identity by reading Pettersson's name live on a
radio broadcast.
   Under Swedish law his name could not be released until the trial
and he has been identified in Swedish media only as ``the
42-year-old.'' Pettersson has a history of drug and alcohol abuse
and a long criminal record.
   During the long investigation into the slaying, police and
security agencies were accused of bungling the case and failing to
turn up credible leads, despite a reward of $8 million. Three
police chiefs and a justice minister resigned at various points in
the investigation.
   Palme, a dynamic and controversial politician, was a U.N.
mediator in the Iran-Iraq war and an advocate of world disarmament.
He led Social Democratic governments in Sweden for 11 years.
   Pettersson was arrested Dec. 14 in a twist to a case that
previously had focused on possible international conspiracies.
   Pettersson, who has a previous manslaughter conviction on a
record sheet of more than 60 crimes, was routinely questioned
during the initial weeks of the investigation, but he was let go.
Pettersson's record includes a conviction for stabbing a man to
death with a bayonet in 1970 just a few steps from where Palme was
killed.
   The prosecution's case relies heavily on the evidence of Lisbet
Palme, the prime minister's widow, who told investigators she
looked for an unforgettable instant into the ``terrifying face'' of
the gunman before he fled.
   But the state attorney lacks a confession, a murder weapon and
an obvious motive, making a conviction by no means a foregone
conclusion.
   The trial, expected to last about six weeks, will be broadcast
extensively on national radio and closely watched by a nation where
terrorism and political assassination had previously been virtually
unknown.
   Two jurors were disqualified last week after being quoted on the
case in a Stockholm newspaper. Defense attorneys challenged their
impartiality and called for their replacement on the panel of six
laymen and two judges.
   A 3,000-page indictment handed down last week said the
prosecution will call 33 witnesses to support their case that
Pettersson stalked the Palmes down Sveavagen Boulevard. Some will
testify he had access to a weapon and lied to investigators about
his whereabouts.
   Defense lawyers, indicated they would question the memory of
witnesses testifying three years after the crime.
</TEXT>
