<FIRST>r a PM-StoreEvacuation     06-05 0222</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Store Evacuation,0227</SECOND>
<HEAD>Thirty-Four Treated for Possible Carbon Monoxide Poisoning</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CONYERS, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Carbon monoxide fumes apparently spewn by a
piece of cleaning equipment sickened more than 50 people at a
crowded supermarket that was celebrating its reopening under new
management, authorities said.
   Of the 34 taken to two hospitals Sunday, six were still there
this morning. Two were listed in satisfactory condition and four
were in stable condition, according to hospital spokespersons.
Others complained of feeling ill but were not taken to hospitals.
   ``People were laying on the sidewalks and in the road,''
Rockdale County Deputy Fire Chief J.R. Magness said Sunday. ``They
were passing out. We had about 15 out at one time.''
   The gas was blamed on a propane-powered floor buffer that had
been used overnight. Magness said fumes circulated through the
store in the air-conditioning system. The store and surrounding
stores in the shopping center were evacuated.
   The accident occurred as a former Piggly Wiggly store reopened
as Bruno's. The grocery store was crowded when employees and
customers began passing out and complaining of headaches, breathing
difficulties and nausea.
   Bruno's Vice President Morrell Dodd confirmed that the buffer
appeared to be the cause.
   ``The explanation at this point is that it was a propane floor
machine. We've never had any trouble with this before,'' Dodd said.
</TEXT>
