<FILEID>AP-NR-06-05-89 1104EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-BridgeRe-Smooted     06-05 0481</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bridge Re-Smooted,0493</SECOND>
<HEAD>The Smoot Is Saved: Fraternity Prank Preserved For Posterity</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SONNI EFRON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CAMBRIDGE, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Smoot is no longer moot.
   The Smoot was invented in 1958 at the Massachusetts Institute of
Technology when freshman fraternity pledges were ordered to measure
the length of Harvard Bridge using only chalk and the body of one
Oliver Reed Smoot Jr. The pranksters manhandled their fellow pledge
end-to-end like a ruler to measure the bridge.
   The bridge markings, maintained by Lambda Chi Alpha pledges for
30 years, threatened to become extinct when the 1891 bridge
recently was slated for a $16.5 million reconstruction.
   However, the Metropolitan District Commission and the Department
of Public Works decided the Smoot should stay when the sidewalk was
replaced.
   ``As a result of the Smoot withstanding the test of time, it has
become part of the folklore of the Harvard Bridge, and as such is
now under the protection of the MDC,'' declared the agency's chief
bridge engineer, David Lenhardt, at a re-Smooting ceremony Sunday.
   On the night of the fraternity prank, the bridge was found to be
364.4 Smoots plus one ear.
   ``Out of the 14 pledges, I had the distinction of being the
shortest,'' explained Smoot, who is 5 feet 7 inches.
   ``And had the best name,'' said Peter S. Miller, who was in
charge of the chalk on that fateful night.
   Twice a year since, freshman pledges have faithfully
``re-Smooted'' the bridge that links MIT with Boston, marking each
10-Smoot length with a gash of paint on the sidewalk.
   The bridge's new sidewalk is scored at 5-foot 7-inch intervals
instead of the usual 6 feet, which will make it easier for future
pledges to repaint their Smoot marks, said Charles Madden, senior
vice president for Martin Continental Construction Co., the
contractor rebuilding the bridge.
   Smoot, now an executive with a trade group in Washington, D.C.,
lay down to have Miller chalk his measure on the new sidewalk.
Although the original deed was done in the dark of night,
interrupted once by a patrolling police car that sent the pledges
scurrying into the shrubs, the re-Smooting was punctuated with
flash bulbs and applause.
   Smoot and his son Stephen, MIT Class of '90, also posed in front
of a bronze plaque that was donated by Smoot's Class of '62 at
their 25th class reunion.
   It reads: ``This plaque placed in honor of the Smoot, which
joined the angstrom, meter and light year as standards of length
when in October, 1958, the span of this bridge was measured using
the body of Oliver Reed Smoot, MIT '62, and found to be precisely
364.4 Smoots and one ear.''
   Reflecting back on the obscure act that has made him a local
legend, Smoot concluded, ``We did it under orders, and we didn't
enjoy it then. But we sure as hell enjoy it now.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890605-0018 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-05-89 1104EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-Scotus-Bookstore     06-05 0503</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Scotus-Bookstore,500</SECOND>
<HEAD>Court Won't Review Case of Merchant Who Sold Sexually Explicit Magazines</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD CARELLI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court today refused to review the
case of an Illinois bookstore owner found guilty of contempt for
violating a law later judged to be unconstitutional.
   The justices, without comment, let stand the contempt finding
against Sequoia Books Inc. in connection with its operation of the
Denmark Bookstore near Aurora, Ill.
   The bookstore, which sells sexually explicit material,
previously had been convicted of selling obscene material when in
1987 it was found to be a public nuisance under state law.
   A state judge issued an order permanently barring the bookstore
from ``maintaining the public nuisance (by) exhibiting, selling or
offering for sale material in the premises'' that would violate the
law.
   Sequoia Books Inc. challenged the permanent injunction as an
impermissible ``prior restraint'' of free speech. While the appeal
was pending, prosecutors sought to have the bookstore closed down
on grounds that it again was selling obscene materials.
   The sale of two magazines, ``Leather Sleaze'' and ``Hard
Leather,'' was cited by the prosecutors, who contended that the
magazines were obscene.
   Sexually explicit material, while often characterized as
pornography, is not necessarily obscene. Obscenity, a legal term,
must be determined in a judicial proceeding.
   If sexually explicit material is obscene, it enjoys no
free-speech protection. If it is not obscene, it is protected by
the free-speech guarantees in the Constitution's First Amendment.
   A state court jury in mid-1987 found that the two magazines were
obscene, and that the Denmark Bookstore therefore had violated the
court order barring it from violating the state's public nuisance
law.
   Sequoia Books Inc. was found guilty of criminal contempt of
court and was fined $10,000.
   On Jan. 19, 1988, a state appeals court ruled for Sequoia Books
in its earlier appeal of the permanent injunction. The appeals
court said the state criminal public nuisance law, when applied to
the bookstore, was an invalid prior restraint on free speech.
   State prosecutors appealed that ruling to the Illinois Supreme
Court, and that appeal is pending.
   Meanwhile, the Denmark Bookstore again was found in contempt of
the judge's order barring violation of public nuisance law. The
bookstore was padlocked for a period of time.
   Last July 21, the same appeals court that invalidated the state
public nuisance law's application to the bookstore upheld the
contempt citations stemming from violations of that law.
   The appeals court rejected Sequoia Books' argument that a
judgment of contempt cannot stand when based on an unconstitutional
injunction.
   The appeals court said the judge's order barring the bookstore
from violating the nuisance law was not ``transparently invalid''
when issued, and therefore could support a contempt finding.
   The state Supreme Court refused to review the contempt issue,
but postponed the appeals court ruling's effect _ a $20,000 fine
and possibly another padlocking _ to allow Sequoia Books a chance
to seek help from the nation's highest court.
   The case is Sequoia Books vs. Illinois, 88-1342.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890605-0019 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-05-89 1109EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w BC-BushTranscript ?Takes   06-05 0828</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Bush Transcript, ? Takes,840-up</SECOND>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here is a transcript of President Bush's
announcement Monday of sanctions against the Chinese government and
his question-and-answer session with reporters afterward:
   Well, during the past few days, elements of the Chinese army
have been brutally suppressing popular and peaceful demonstrations
in China. There's been widespread and continuing violence, many
casualties, and many deaths.
   And we deplore the decision to use force, and I now call on the
Chinese leadership publicly, as I have in private channels, to
avoid violence and to return to their previous policy of restraint.
   The demonstrators in Tiananmen Square were advocating basic
human rights, including the freedom of expression, freedom of the
press, freedom of association. These are goals we support around
the world.
   These are freedoms that are enshrined in both the US
Constitution and the Chinese constitution. Throughout the world, we
stand with those who seek greater freedom and democracy. This is
the strongly felt view of my administration, of our Congress, and
most important, of the American people.
   In recent weeks, we've urged mutual restraint, nonviolence, and
dialogue; instead, there has been a violent and bloody attack on
the demonstrators. The United States cannot condone the violent
attacks and cannot ignore the consequences for our relationship
with China, which has been built on a foundation of broad support
by the American people.
   This is not the time for an emotional response, but for a
reasoned, careful action, that takes into account both our
long-term interests and recognition of a complex internal situation
in China.
   There clearly is turmoil within the ranks of the political
leadership, as well as the political _ the People's Liberation
Army. And now is the time to look beyond the moment to important
and enduring aspects of this vital relationship for the United
States. Indeed, the budding of democracy which we have seen in
recent weeks owes much to the relationship we have developed since
1972.
   And it's important at this time to act in a way that will
encourage the further development and deepening of the positive
elements of that relationship and the process of democratization.
It would be a tragedy for all if China were to pull back to its
pre-1972 era of isolation and repression.
   Mindful of these complexities and yet of the necessity to
strongly and clearly express our condemnation of the events of
recent days, I'm ordering the following actions:
   _Suspension of all government-to-government sales and commercial
exports of weapons.
   _Suspension of visits between US and Chinese military leaders.
   _Sympathic review of requests by Chinese students in the United
States to extend their stay.
   _And the offer of humanitarian and medical assistance, through
the Red Cross, to those injured during the assault.
   _And review of other aspects of our bilateral relationship as
events in China continue to unfold.
   The process of democratization of communist societies will not
be a smooth one, and we must react to setbacks in a way which
stimulates rather than stifles progress toward open and
representative systems.
   And I'd be glad to take a few questions before our Cabinet
meeting which starts in a few minutes. I think _ I can't remember
who's first here. Tom?
   Q: Yes, Mr. President, you have said _
   Bush: And then Helen.
   Q: You have said the genie of democracy cannot be put back in
the bottle in China. You said that, however, before the actions of
the past weekend. Do you still believe that? And are there further
steps that the United States could take, such as economic
sanctions, to further democracy in China?
   Bush: Yes, I still believe that. I believe the forces of
democracy are so powerful, and when you see them, as recently as
this morning _ a single student standing in front of a tank, and
then, I might add, seeing the tank driver exercise restraint _ I'm
convinced that the forces of democracy are going to overcome these
unfortunate events in Tiananmen Square.
   On the commercial side, I don't want to hurt the Chinese people.
I happen to believe that commercial contacts have led, in essence,
to this quest for more freedom. I think as people have commercial
incentive, whether it's in China or in other totalitarian systems,
the move to democracy becomes more inexorable.
   So what we have done is suspended certain things on the military
side, and my concern is with those in the military who are using
force. And yet when I some exercising restraint, and see the big
divisions that exist inside the PLA, I am _ I think we need to move
along the lines I've outlined here.
   I think that it's important to keep saying to those elements in
the Chinese military, ``Restraint. Continue to show the restraint
that many of you have shown.'' And I understand there are deep
divisions inside the Army. So this is -- we're putting the emphasis
on that side of it.
   Yes, Helen.
</TEXT>
