<FIRST>r w PM-Scotus-Hunting     06-05 0443</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Scotus-Hunting,440</SECOND>
<HEAD>Court Refuses To Reinstate Connecticut Law Protecting Hunters</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD CARELLI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court today refused to reinstate a
Connecticut law that protected hunters against ``harassment'' and
``interference.''
   The justices, without comment, let stand a federal appeals court
ruling that the 1985 state law was so broad and vague that it
violated free-speech rights.
   Francelle Dorman of Niantic, Conn., was arrested Jan. 30, 1986,
and charged with violating the law.
   Her arrest occured during goose-hunting season on state forest
property located near her home.
   Ms. Dorman, described in court documents as someone opposed to
the hunting and killing of animals, had approached several hunters
in marshlands and tried to dissuade them from hunting any waterfowl.
   According to the court documents, Ms. Dorman ``walked with the
hunters ... spoke to them about the violence and cruelty of
hunting, of the beauty of the waterfowl, and (of) their right to
live peacefully and without harm.''
   When Ms. Dorman refused to leave, the hunters summoned a law
enforcement officer who arrested her.
   The criminal charges against her _ violation of the state's
Hunter Harassment Act was a misdemeanor _ later were dropped when
prosecutors concluded that her arrest had been premature. They said
Ms. Dorman only talked about what she was going to do to interfere
with hunting for geese.
   But Ms. Dorman nevertheless sued in federal court three months
after her arrest, seeking to have the law struck down. She
contended that her arrest and the threat of future enforcement of
the 1985 law violated her free-speech rights.
   A federal judge agreed and struck down the law as too vague and
overbroad.
   The 2nd U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals upheld that ruling last
Dec. 7 after turning down a request by prosecutors that the
Connecticut Supreme Court be given a chance to interpet exactly
what forms of harassment and interference would be prohibited.
   ``The Connecticut court would be in no better position than a
federal court to decide which interpretation is correct,'' the 2nd
Circuit court said, ``because (the law) is so imprecise and
indefinite it is subject to any number of interpretations.''
   The law made it a crime for anyone to ``interfere with the
lawful taking of wildlife by another person'' or to ``harass
another person who is engaged in the lawful taking of wildlife or
acts in preparation for such taking.''
   The appeals court said, ``The terms `interfere,' `harass' and
`acts in preparation' ... can mean anything.''
   The offices of the Connecticut attorney general and the chief
state's attorney then sought help from the nation's highest court.
   The case is Satti vs. Dorman, 88-1743.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
