<DOCNO> AP890605-0023 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-05-89 1120EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w PM-Bush-ForeignPolicy 1st-LdWritethru a0417 06-05 0886</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bush-Foreign Policy, 1st-Ld Writethru, a0417,950</SECOND>
<HEAD>New Challenges in the International Arena Await Bush</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDs: New thruout with Bush news conference.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUSANNE M. SCHAFER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In Washington, the applause never lasts for
long.
   President Bush, fresh from his triumphant debut on the stage of
international foreign policy at the NATO summit, has come home to
face the twin challenges posed by the violence in China and the
shifting balance of power in Tehran.
   The gusto Bush showed in forging a compromise among the
irascible North Atlantic Treaty Organization allies has been
replaced with cautious steps in response to the bloody repression
of students in China.
   Early today, Bush announced he was halting U.S. weapons sales to
China and offering humantarian aid through the international Red
Cross to those injured in the supression of demonstrations in China
over the weekend.
   ``My conviction is that this is not a time for anything other
than a prudent, reasoned response...This is not the time for an
emotional response,'' Bush said in explaining to reporters in the
White House briefing room why he was not taking stronger action.
``I don't want to see a total break in this relationship and I will
not encourage a total break in this relationship.''
   Bush, who ran for the presidency touting his foreign policy
expertise, was buffeted by members of his own party, who demanded a
tough, retaliatory response to the Chinese brutalities.
   ``It's folly,'' sniffed Sen. Jesse Helms, R-N.C. ``We need to
stand with these young people who are trying to achieve freedom.''
   Somehow, it seemed so much easier when Bush dealt with the NATO
leaders in Brussels last week. With them, he shared a common
celebration of their democratic values and the 40th anniversary of
their pact against fascism.
   There, America's new president grabbed the international stage
with his sweeping proposals for cuts in conventional weapons and
the compromise on short-range nuclear weapons.
   But in Iran, in the wake of the Khomeini's rule, Bush must deal
with a nation that deeply embarrassed his Oval Office predecessors
and stymied U.S. foreign policy as it held Americans hostage.
   And China's explosion of violence over the weekend provided a
stark display of the difficulty a major superpower faces in
attempting to influence another foreign nation.
   For weeks, the United States had appealed for calm and respect
for the expressions of democracy in China.
   Secretary of State James A. Baker III repeated those admonitions
yet again on Saturday, even as the bullets began to fly in
Tiananmen Square.
   After hearing a live report of the massacre from a reporter on
the scene with the sounds of ambulances echoing in the background,
Baker's statement's took a sharper tone. He called the situation
``extremely deplorable'' and said the developments would arouse the
concern of the U.S. government and people.
   Later, the White House issued a statement in Bush's name, saying
he ``deeply'' deplored the decision ``to use force against peaceful
demonstrators and the consequent loss of life.''
   He urged Beijing to use non-violent tactics, expressing the hope
that China ``will rapidly return to the path of political and
economic reform and conditions of stability so that this
relationship (between the United States and China), so important to
both our peoples, can continue its growth.''
   During Bush's trip to China earlier this year, he was hailed as
an ``old friend,'' of the country, where he'd served as one of the
first U.S. envoys to the People's Republic.
   If Bush's actions were not as vigorous as some might like, he
promised to monitor the situation and take further steps if
necessary.
   ``It reserve the right to take a whole new look at things if the
violence escalates,'' Bush said today.
   But now he treads cautiously, because a lot is at stake.
   Does the United States turn on the 10-year relationship that has
blossomed since formal ties were reached in 1979? Do the friendly
relations, thousands of student exchanges, the $13.7 billion
two-way trade now wither and die?
   If Bush chooses, several actions are possible.
   He could recall U.S. Ambassador James Lilley for consultations
to show disapproval. He could suspend the transfer of
high-technology items or revoke the recently renewed
most-favored-nation trading status that has helped China become the
United States 13th largest trading partner.
   Currently, U.S. firms have been investing in China to the tune
of $3 billion annually.
   He also could break relations with Beijing _ an unlikely
possibility.
   It is questionable what effect sanctions would have.
   Rep. Stephen Solarz, D-N.Y., acknowledged on Sunday that the
U.S. ability to influence the course of events in China ``is very
limited.''
   But Solarz, who appeared with Helms on CBS-TV's ``Face the
Nation,'' said he believed that ``much more is at stake. ... What
is involved ... is our capacity to credibly maintain our leadership
of the movement for democracy and human rights around the world.
   ``And if we appear to be indifferent or insensitive to the human
rights of one-fifth of the human race, then I think it'll be very
difficult for us to plausibly contend that we are in favor of
democracy and human rights all over the world.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Susanne M. Schafer is a former foreign
correspondent for The Associated Press now covering the State
Department.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
