<FILEID>AP-NR-06-05-89 1123EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-Scotus-Frey     06-05 0338</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Scotus-Frey,330</SECOND>
<HEAD>Court Refuses to Delay Pennsylvanian's Execution, But Death Already
Delayed</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD CARELLI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court today refused to postpone a
Pennsylvania death row inmate's execution but, in a strange twist
of events, a lower federal court already had granted a postponement.
   The justices, by a 5-4 vote, denied an emergency request filed
on behalf of Roderick Frey, whose June 13 execution was to make him
the first to die in Pennsylvania's electric chair since 1962.
   But a federal judge, acting on a separate emergency request,
granted an indefinite stay of execution last week.
   The Supreme Court request had been filed before the federal
judge acted.
   Frey, 52, was convicted of arranging the Nov. 8, 1979 killing of
his wife, Barbara Jean. She was fatally shot while driving to work
in Lancaster County.
   Frey confessed to hiring Charles Zehring for the murder. The
couple's divorce was pending at the time.
   The nation's highest court already has agreed to review the
constitutionality of Pennsylvania's death penalty law. A decision
is expected during the court term that will begin next October.
   A still-pending formal appeal filed on Frey's behalf raises the
issue the court already is studying: Whether the state law
improperly limits the discretion of juries in choosing life or
death for convicted killers.
   Under Pennsylvania's law, a jury must impose the death penalty
if it ``unanimously finds at least one aggravating circumstance ...
and no mitigating circumstance.''
   The justices are being urged to rule that the state law results
in impermissible mandatory death sentences.
   The Pennsylvania Supreme Court rejected that argument last
October when it upheld the death penalty law.
   State officials contend the state law is constitutional because,
despite its mandatory language, nothing prevents a defendant from
presenting any and all mitigating evidence to offset any
aggravating circumstance.
   Dissenting from today's one-sentence order denying Frey's
emergency request were Justices William J. Brennan, Thurgood
Marshall, Harry A. Blackmun and John Paul Stevens.
   The case is Frey vs. Pennsylvania, A-914.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890605-0025 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-05-89 1126EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w BC-BushTranscript 1stAdd   06-05 0978</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Bush Transcript, 1st Add,960</SECOND>
<HEAD>WASHN: Yes, Helen.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Q: Have you had personal contact with the Chinese leadership?
Why do you think they moved in the way they did? And why did you
wait so long?
   Bush: Well, I don't think we've waited so long, Helen. We've
been _I made very clear, in a personal communication to Deng
Xiaoping, my views on this. I talked to the Ambassador last night,
Jim Lilley. We've been in _ he's been in touch constantly with the
Chinese officials, and so, I can't _ I don't feel that we've waited
long, when you have a force of this nature, and you have events of
this nature unfolding.
   We are the United States and they are China, and what I want to
do is continue to urge freedom, democracy, respect, non-violence,
and with great admiration in my heart for the students. So, I don't
think we've waited long. What was the other part of your question?
   Q: What impelled the Chinese government? They did wait a long
time, more than we expected really, and _
   Bush: Yes, they did.
   Q: Then they finally moved in. What do you think is the _
   Bush: We were urging _ that's a _ I'm glad you raised that
point. We were, and have been, and will continue to urge restraint,
and they did _ the army did show restraint. When Wan Li was here,
he told me, and this is very Chinese the way he expressed it, the
army loves the Chinese people.
   And they showed restraint for a long time, and I don't _ I can't
begin to fathom for you exactly what led to the order to use force
because, even as recently as a couple of days ago, there was
evidence that the military were under orders not to use force. So,
I think we have to wait now until that unfolds. Yeah, Brit.
   Q: Mr. President, could you give us your current, best
assessment of the political situation there _ which leaders are up,
which are down, who apparently has prevailed here, and who
apparently has lost?
   Bush: It's too obscure, it's too beclouded to say. And I would
remind you of this history. In the Cultural Revolution days, Deng
Xiaoping, at Mao Zedong's right hand, was put out; he came back in
1976. He was put out again in the last days of Mao Zedong and the
days of the Gang of Four.
   Then he came back in, and to his credit, he moved China towards
openness, towards democracy, towards reform. And suddenly we see a
reversal, and I don't think there is anybody in this country that
can answer your question with authority at this point. It doesn't
work that way in dealing with China.
   Q: Mr. President, there have been reports that Deng was behind
the move to order the troops, and other reports that he's ailing
and in a hospital. What do you know about that, sir?
   Bush: No, don't know for sure on either, and I've talked to our
ambassador on that _ as I say, last night _ and we just can't
confirm one way or another on the other. Yes?
   Q: Mr. President, you spoke of the need for the US to maintain
relations with China. But given the brutality of the attacks over
the last couple of days, can the US ever return to business as
usual with the current regime?
   Bush: I don't want to see a total break in this relationship,
and I will not encourage a total break in the relationship.
   This relationship is _ when you see these kids struggling for
democracy and freedom, this would be a bad time for the United
States to withdraw and pull back and leave them to the devices of a
leadership that might decide to crack down further.
   I do _ some have suggested I take the ambassador out. In my
view, that would be 180 degrees wrong. Our ambassador provides one
of the best listening posts we have in China. He is thoroughly
experienced. And so let others make proposals that in my view don't
make much sense.
   I want to see us stay involved and continue to work for
restraint and for human rights and for democracy. And then down the
road, we have enormous commonality of interest with China, but it
will not be the same under a brutal and repressive regime. So I
stop short of suggesting that what we ought to do is break
relations with China, and I would like to encourage them to
continue their change. Yes?
   Q: Mr. Bush, you're sending a message to the military and to the
government. A couple of weeks ago you told the students to continue
to stand by their beliefs. What message do you want the students to
hear from what you're saying right now?
   Bush: That we support their quest for democracy, for reform, and
for freedom. And there should be no doubt about that. And then in
sending this message to the military, I would encourage them to go
back to the posture of a few days ago that did show restraint, and
that did recognize the rights of the people, and that did epitomize
what that Chinese leader told me, that the army loves the people.
There's still vivid examples of that.
   Q: Should the students go home? Should the students stop trying
to _
   Bush: I can't dictate to the students what they should do from
half way around the world. But we support the quest for democracy
and reform, that this relationship is vital to the United States of
America, and so is our adherence to democracy and our encouragement
for those who are willing to hold high the banner of democracy. So
we've found, I think, a prudent path here.
   Yes?
</TEXT>
