<FIRST>r a PM-FernaldTrial 2ndLd-Writethru a0509 06-05 0443</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Fernald Trial, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0509, a0546,0448</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lawsuit Over Uranium-Plant's Damage Goes to `Summary Trial'</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 3rd graf, `Final arguments...', to UPDATE with jurors selected.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CINCINNATI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An unusual, non-binding trial is intended to
help settle a $300 million lawsuit brought by the neighbors of a
government uranium-processing plant in a case that might otherwise
take weeks in court.
   U.S. District Judge S. Arthur Spiegel is presiding over the
``summary trial'' to encourage an agreement in the class-action
suit representing about 14,000 people who live within five miles of
the Feed Materials Production Center in Fernald, Ohio.
   Eight jurors were selected for the trial this morning, and the
court was briefly recessed before opening arguments were to begin.
The trial was expected to last about a week, with final arguments
set to begin next Monday.
   The residents charge that the plant, owned by the Energy
Department and operated from 1951 to 1985 by National Lead of Ohio
Inc., contaminated the air, water and soil with uranium, radium and
thorium as well as dangerous non-radioactive substances including
asbestos, chlorids and barium.
   The plant processed uranium for use in the government's nuclear
weapons. National Lead and its parent firm, National Lead
Industries, are named in the suit. Residents claim the plant 18
miles northwest of Cincinnati caused them emotional stress and
lowered property values.
   The Energy Department denies the allegations but has begun a
cleanup program and admitted that more than 300,000 pounds of
radioactive uranium oxide dust escaped into the atmosphere through
faulty air-filtering systems.
   Cincinnati lawyer Stanley M. Chesley, representing the
plaintiffs, said he considers the summary trial a useful tool for
encouraging a settlement, which Chesley said the Energy Department
had been unwilling to negotiate.
   ``We're finally going to hear the story of Fernald. We're
finally going to have it in a court of law,'' Chesley said. ``We
think it's a wonderful opportunity to resolve a dispute.''
   Energy Department lawyer Henry A. Gill Jr. declined to say
whether the department would be willing to settle the case.
   The Energy Department contends that the companies are innocent
because they were contractors following the government's orders.
The department has conceded it told National Lead to emphasize
production, even if that meant ignoring some environmental
regulations.
   Gill said he would not regard the verdict of the summary trial
as final.
   ``Absolutely not. It's, by its very nature, a non-binding
verdict. It's a settlement tool that some judges like to avoid
using,'' Gill said.
   But Chesley said: ``It's not binding, but in my estimation, it
becomes very significant. I think this is the utmost conflict
resolution method that we know about.''
</TEXT>
