<FIRST>d a PM-BRF--Jogger     06-05 0174</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-BRF--Jogger,0178</SECOND>
<HEAD>Report Says Attack Victim Being Moved To Pittsburgh</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The jogger raped and beaten in Central Park
seven weeks ago is expected to be moved soon to a neurological
rehabilitation center near her parents' home in Pittsburgh,
according to a published report.
   A spokeswoman for Metropolitan Hospital, however, said she could
not confirm the report in this week's Newsweek. ``We spoke to the
doctors and they did not confirm it to us this morning,'' said
Myrna Rodriguez of the hospital's public relations office.
   The 28-year-old woman, an Ivy League-educated investment banker,
has continued showing improvement since coming out of a coma, but
doctors say she probably will never return to normal.
   She has for the first time begun asking questions about the
attack on her, and city investigators are planning to talk to her
soon, according to one of her doctors.
   While the woman has been able to have brief conversations,
recognize visitors and tell jokes, she can so far read only the
most simple sentences, Newsweek said.
