<FIRST>r w PM-Scotus-Sculpture     06-05 0500</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Scotus-Sculpture,500</SECOND>
<HEAD>Court Says Group Does Not Own Sculpture's Copyright Exclusively</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court, in a victory for artists
and authors, said today a homeless-rights group does not own
exclusively the copyright to a sculpture it commissioned an artist
to create.
   The 9-0 decision ordered further lower court hearings to
determine whether the Community for Creative Non-Violence (CCNV)
and its founder, Mitch Snyder, may share in the copyright of a work
entitled ``Third World America'' that depicts the plight of the
homeless.
   Justice Thurgood Marshall, writing for the court, said the
sculpture is a ``work made for hire'' and therefore its creator,
James Earl Reid of Baltimore, must at least share in the copyright.
   Marshall said CCNV did not become the copyright owner just
because it played an active role in designing the work and may
control its display. Reid is a free-lance artist, not an employee
of CCNV, he said.
   ``Transforming a commissioned work into a work by an employee on
the basis of the hiring party's right to control ... the work is
inconsistent with ... the work-for-hire provisions'' of a 1976
federal copyright law, Marshall said.
   CCNV, based in the nation's capital, decided in 1985 to
participate in the annual Christmas Pageant of Peace here by having
Reid help create a display dramatizing the plight of the homeless.
   Reid, using a synthetic substance tinted to resemble bronze,
scuplted two adult figures and a child huddled on a streetside
steam grate.
   The life-sized figures were intended as part of an updated
Nativity scene.
   CCNV provided a steam grate and pedestal for the work.
   Reid was paid $15,000 for expenses and for his assistants. He
donated his own services without charge.
   CCNV sent the entire sculpture back to Reid in January 1986 for
some repairs.
   The group planned to take the sculpture on a tour of several
cities to raise money for the homeless.
   But Reid objected to the tour because, he said, the sculpture
was too fragile. He urged CCNV to cast the work in bronze or make a
master mold that would withstand the tour.
   CCNV declined, but said Reid could do so if he wished.
   Two months later, Reid refused to return the sculpture and
registered it in his own name. He also said he planned to take the
work on a less ambitious exhibition tour.
   CCNV then filed a lawsuit claiming exclusive copyright ownership
of the sculpture.
   A federal judged ruled in favor of the organization. But the
U.S. Court of Appeals here overturned the judge's decision,
ordering further hearings in the dispute to determine whether CCNV
is entitled to share in the copyright.
   A group representing more than 100,000 artists and authors urged
the Supreme Court to uphold the appeals court decision.
   The reputation and income of free-lance artists depends on their
ability to own the copyrights of their works, the group said.
   The case is Community for Creative Non-Violence vs. Reid, 88-293.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890605-0032 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-05-89 1155EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Namibia     06-05 0389</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Namibia,0401</SECOND>
<HEAD>South African, U.N. Officials Agree on Return of Refugees</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HEIDI VON EGIDY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WINDHOEK, Namibia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   South African and U.N. officials said
today they reached a tentative agreement to scrap discriminatory
laws in Namibia and clear the way for more than 40,000 Namibian
refugees to begin returning home.
   Officials said Pretoria agreed to abolish remaining
discriminatory laws in Namibia, end detentions without trial, and
provide amnesty for black nationalist guerrillas who have fought
for 23 years to oust South Africa from this mineral-rich territory.
   Louis Pienaar, South African-appointed administrator of Namibia,
and U.N. envoy Martti Ahtisaari reached the agreement on the
discriminatory laws last week, according to their spokesmen.
   South African President P.W. Botha was to sign legislation
enacting the accords today or Tuesday, the spokesmen said.
   ``With the signing by President Botha, the U.N. high
commissioner for refugees will be told immediately to start the
repatriation of refugees,'' said U.N. spokesman Fred Eckhardt.
   U.N. officials have registered 41,000 Namibian refugees in
Angola and Zambia who could start returning home early next week,
officials said.
   South Africa, which has ruled the territory for 74 years, agreed
to a U.N. independence plan that began April 1 and will lead to
November elections.
   Returning refugees will include members of the South-West Africa
People's Organization, which is widely favored to win the
elections. It is unclear, however, if the organization will be able
to capture the two-thirds majority necessary to control a new
government.
   Campaigning is to begin July 1, but none of the movement's
senior exiled leaders has returned.
   Several matters remain unresolved, including voter registration
procedures and the release of political prisoners. Pienaar and
Ahtisaari met today and will meet again to discuss these questions,
their spokesmen said.
   Namibian authorities say they hold 29 political prisoners, while
the guerrilla organization says authorities recently released 201
dissidents.
   More than 4,000 U.N. personnel are in Namibia to monitor the
transition to independence.
   Under the plan, South Africa has withdrawn 46,000 of its troops,
leaving less than 4,000 in Namibia. That number should be reduced
to 1,500 by June 20, the military said.
   Namibia's independence is part of a regional peace plan signed
by Pretoria in exchange for the removal of some 50,000 Cuban troops
helping Angola's government fight right-wing rebels backed by
Washington and Pretoria.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
