<FIRST>u a PM-UMW-Pittston     06-05 0269</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-UMW-Pittston,0277</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge Jails Three UMW Officials for Contempt of Court</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ABINGDON, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge today ordered three United
Mine Workers strike organizers jailed for violating his ban on
sit-down demonstrations designed to block coal delivery trucks.
   U.S. District Judge Glen Williams said his May 24 order
prohibiting the demonstrations against Pittston Coal Group had been
ignored, and found strike coordinators Marty Hudson, Jackie Stump
and C.A. Phillips in contempt of court. About 1,500 miners in
Virginia and West Virginia have been on strike against Pittston
since April 5, after a year of working without a contract.
   Evidence presented last week showed the three UMW officials
orchestrated the sit-down demonstrations in front of Pittston's
mines and coal plants, the judge said.
   The defendants, taking the 5th Amendment, declined to testify on
their own behalf, saying their statements might be used against
them in other strike-related court cases.
   Stump did tell the judge that he had tried everything he could
to make sure the strike remained peaceful and that he will continue
to do so.
   Williams told the three officials that they will remain in jail
until they promise to halt the illegal strike activity.
   ``The purpose of this hearing was to get obedience to my order,
in other words, undo what you have done,'' he said. ``The purpose
of sending you to jail is not to punish you but to make sure you
comply with my order.''
   On Friday, a state judge, Circuit Court Judge Donald McLaughlin,
fined the union $3 million for breaking his ban on mass picketing
and sit-down demonstrations in southwestern Virginia.
</TEXT>
