<FIRST>r a AM-Seals'Meals     06-05 0180</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Seals' Meals,0185</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sea Mammals Gobbling Expensive Salmon</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEWPORT, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hungry seals and sea lions are dining on
salmon off Oregon and fish experts say residents are picking up the
check.
   Harbor seals and California sea lions have flourished since the
federal Marine Mammal Protection Act was adopted in 1972, but
Oregon fishemen say it's time to control the population.
   The Oregon Department of Fish and Wildlife estimates there are
5,000 to 7,000 harbor seals in state waters, double the population
in the mid-1970s. Biologists say the sea lion population has
increased by one-third since 1972.
   The seals and sea lions cruise the river estuaries for salmon
returning from the ocean to spawn.
   ``A seal eats about 25 pounds of fish a day,'' wildlife
biologist John Johnson says. ``If you multiply the number of seals
in the bay times 365 days a year, that's a staggering figure.''
   Tom Robinson, manager of the Oregon Salmon Commission, says each
10-pound chinook represents $75 to Oregon's economy, and each
five-pound coho represents $35.
   ``That's a fairly expensive meal,'' he says.
</TEXT>
