<FILEID>AP-NR-06-05-89 1223EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-DeSotoSearch     06-05 0338</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-De Soto Search,0345</SECOND>
<HEAD>Archaeologists Search for De Soto's Camp</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COLUMBUS, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Archaeologists planned to begin scouring
parts of northern Mississippi on Tuesday in search of the
16th-century trail of Spanish explorer Hernando De Soto and his
expedition's 1540-41 winter campsite.
   ``Our ultimate goal is to find the campsite,'' said University
of Mississippi archaeologist Jay Johnson, who will lead the team.
``And from that we could figure out a lot more about De Soto's
expedition, including the spot where he crossed the Tombigbee
River.''
   Some researchers think the crossing is between Aberdeen and the
site of the old Nashville Ferry, an area that includes Columbus.
   The campsite was the scene of a March 1541 battle in which
Chickasaw Indians destroyed much of the Spaniards' supply train and
killed 49 men. The Indians called the place ``Chicasa.''
   Researchers requested the help of a NASA airplane equipped with
infrared sensors in an effort to locate the campsite. The sensors
can detect heat differences between normal land and phosphate
deposits that characterize inhabited sites.
   ``But if we're going to do aerial surveys, we need to do them
before September,'' Johnson said. ``Once crops start coming in,
it's hard to see the ground, and we want to cover as much ground as
possible.''
   Johnson spoke Friday at the first meeting of the Mississippi De
Soto Commission at the Columbus Convention Center. The state
commission is one of 10 in the Southeast trying to pin down and
mark the path of De Soto's 1539-1542 explorations, which included
the first European sighting of the Mississippi River.
   ``We have the responsibility of erecting markers to signal the
exploration, and then planning events commemorating the
expedition,'' said Elbert Hilliard, director of the state
Department of Archives and History.
   ``We want to promote scholarly, archaeological and historical
research that results in more information on this expedition and
its impact on the history of our region,'' he said.
   The 34-member commission is funded by private donations, and
includes a representative from all eight state colleges.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890605-0039 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-05-89 1225EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-AIDSInsurance Bjt   06-05 0725</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-AIDS Insurance, Bjt,0743</SECOND>
<HEAD>New Program To Pay Private Insurance for AIDS Victims</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LISA ZAGAROLI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LANSING, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Michigan hopes to save millions of dollars
with a new program designed to keep AIDS victims off the Medicaid
rolls by paying their private insurance premiums.
   The two-year pilot program, given final legislative approval
last week, is already being discussed by other states and likely
will be copied if it proves successful, said state Rep. David
Hollister.
   ``The program is aimed at someone who has a job, has insurance,
and at some point they lose their job because of their illness,''
said Hollister, who got the idea for the program while attending a
workshop of the National Academy of Science on insurance companies
and AIDS.
   ``They can continue their insurance for up to 18 months at their
own expense after they lose their job, but most people don't have
18 months of reserves to pay that,'' he said. ``So at a certain
point they're going to lose their insurance, and at that point they
become impoverished and we pay it out of Medicaid.''
   The cost of treating a person with acquired immune deficiency
syndrome in Michigan is about $1,600 a month. The state share of
Medicaid expenditures usually is about 45 percent, or $724.
   Insurance premiums vary with different policies; the average
cost of a health plan offered to state employees is about $135 a
month.
   If an AIDS patient becomes too sick to work and continue paying
insurance premiums, Medicaid could save about $1,465 a month per
person by paying the private insurance premium.
   The state predicts about 180 people will participate in the
program this year, saving the state about $323,000; 370 in 1990,
saving $2.6 million; and 580 in 1992, saving $4.1 million.
   It is scheduled to start Oct. 1 as a three-county experiment in
the metropolitan Detroit counties of Wayne, Oakland and Macomb,
which are home to about 70 percent of the state's AIDS-infected
population.
   ``The trickiest part is to make sure the state only pays the
premiums for the people who would have become Medicaid eligible,''
said Scott Merwin, a senior analyst with the Department of Social
Service's Medicaid division, who wrote the proposal with Hollister.
   Most people would become eligible for the program after they
have lost their jobs and their disability insurance has expired.
   Critics say that the plan takes into account only participants'
incomes, not assets, and that the largest growing population of
AIDS carriers _ intravenous drug users _ likely never had insurance
at all.
   Robert Lundy, legislative officer for the Michigan Organization
for Human Rights, a homosexual-lesbian group based in Detroit, said
he was pleased with the program but didn't think it went far
enough, noting it only covered three counties.
   The insurance industry, which has the most to lose with the
setup, has responded mildly.
   ``An in-force insurance policy is an in-force insurance policy.
If an AIDS patient borrows the money from Uncle Harry, that policy
is good,'' said Robert Waldron, director of the New York office of
the Health Insurance Association of America. The trade association
represents about 85 percent of the commercial health insurers in
the country.
   ``They're obliged to pay. That's the business they're in. In
fact, our advice has been, `Hang on to that insurance policy. Beg,
borrow, try not to steal, but hang on to that insurance policy.'
Why should we complain?'' Waldron asked.
   Even Blue Cross and Blue Shield of Michigan, which has to take
all comers regardless of illness, backs the idea.
   ``This seems to be a fairly restricted approach and it's aimed
at just those AIDS patients who have insurance already,'' said
Dennis Larson, public relations coordinator for the company. ``It
doesn't lead me down the road to believe the state's going to be
recruiting AIDS patients to get on insurance.''
   As of May 8, 1,120 cases of AIDS had been reported in Michigan
since 1981, and 650 of those patients had died. The Centers for
Disease Control in Atlanta reported that as of April 30, there were
90,280 cases nationwide, and 54,402 of those people died.
   AIDS weakens the body's immune system and leaves it susceptible
to cancers and infections. It is transferred through the exchange
of body fluids, most often through sexual intercourse and sharing
contaminated hypodermic needle or syringes.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
