<FIRST>u i AM-China-Chaos Bjt   06-05 0565</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-China-Chaos, Bjt,0583</SECOND>
<HEAD>Food, Work and Transportation Grow Scarce Amid Chaos</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-China, Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>By TERRIL JONES</HEAD>
<HEAD>Associated Press Writer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The army's attack on pro-democracy demonstrators
has thrown the Chinese capital into chaos. Most public
transportation is suspended, soldiers patrol the streets and food
shortages are developing.
   The army's unexpectedly brutal attacks on students and their
sympathizers during the weekend, and soldiers' continuing rampage
through the streets of Beijing, have disrupted normal life.
   ``All we have to eat are instant noodles, and the only way we
can get anywhere is by bicycle,'' said a worker in his 30s.
   Lines already are forming for such staples as milk, oil, salt,
soy sauce and coal gas for cooking. With the military's blockade of
major access roads to Beijing, suppliers are finding it difficult
if not impossible to enter the city, and fruits, vegetables and
meat have increased 40-50 percent in price.
   Tens of thousands of soldiers stormed Tiananmen Square Saturday
night and early Sunday to disperse student-led protesters who had
occupied the square since May 13. Hundreds, perhaps thousands, were
believed shot, beaten or crushed to death.
   Soldiers periodically charge out from the square with their guns
blazing. At least eight people were reported shot Monday, three
fatally.
   There have been scattered calls for a general strike. But with
People's Liberation Army soldiers roaming the streets and firing
randomly at buildings and people, few are showing up at their jobs
anyway.
   ``What are we going to do, go to work and get shot?'' asked an
office clerk.
   ``We have no guarantee for the safety of our lives,'' said a
36-year-old Communist Party official. ``We don't want to overthrow
the government, but we never thought the government could be so
inhumane.''
   A senior at Beijing's No. 65 High School joined the chorus.
``We're afraid to walk the streets,'' he said. ``We never know when
some plainclothes policeman or a soldier will shoot us in the
back.''
   With nowhere to go, people are streaming onto the streets
despite the danger, to share what they've seen and heard, gawk at
bullet holes and vent their outrage at the government for ordering
the slaughter.
   ``What we need are United Nations peacekeeping forces here,'' a
40-year-old man said. ``They would be warmly welcomed.''
   A senior from Beijing Commercial College complained the citywide
disruption could keep her from graduating. ``There's no way I can
do research for my senior thesis,'' she said.
   Changan Avenue, Beijing's main road, was strewn with discarded
shoes, chunks of bricks, gutted remains of burnt-out buses and
mangled traffic dividers crushed by tanks.
   The gates were locked at the Beijing Hotel, two blocks from
Tiananmen, and guests had to climb over them to get inside. At the
posh International Hotel, also on Changan Avenue, one worker said
only 30 percent of the staff was on duty.
   ``I've been working for 48 hours straight since there's no staff
to relieve me,'' he said. The hotel was only serving cheese and ham
sandwiches, he said.
   A receptionist at the Capital Hotel, also near the square, said
there were no guests left and that employees were staying at the
hotel because they were afraid to go home.
   The Mengchuan Restaurant, a small place facing the wide
thoroughfare, closed Saturday after the troops entered the square.
   A few workers showed up nevertheless, spending their time
watching tanks go by.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
