<FIRST>r a PM-MedicalDivorce     06-05 0344</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Medical Divorce,0352</SECOND>
<HEAD>Couple Divorces So Wife Can Get Nursing Care</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By J.L. SCHMIDT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LINCOLN, Neb. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge today issued a divorce decree for a
Methodist minister who said he wanted to end his marriage to his
paralyzed wife of 32 years so she could afford nursing care.
   ``Our system is such that we must impoverish people so they can
afford necessary nursing care,'' lawyer Virginia Johnson said after
Lancaster County Judge Paul Merritt issued the decree for the Rev.
Lincoln B. Justice and his wife, Rose Marie.
   ``This is not uncommon,'' said Johnson, who represented Mrs.
Justice, 56.
   After Mrs. Justice was paralyzed from the neck down in an
automobile accident 10 years ago, the couple had a specially
designed wheelchair-accessible home built and coped using homemaker
services.
   But Justice told Merritt today that his wife's bout with
pneumonia in January left her in need of 24-hour care.
   ``I can't work and provide that care,'' Justice said.
   Under a property settlement approved by the court, Mrs. Justice
will remain in the Lincoln home. Justice told reporters he expects
to live in Weeping Water, where he has been transferred, and visit
his ex-wife about once a week. The town is about 35 miles away.
   ``Financial reasons were the main stress in this marriage,''
Johnson said. ``Rather than impoverish both husband and wife, this
will allow her to spend down her assets, remain in her home and be
eligible for Medicaid.''
   Johnson said that if the couple had remained married, Medicaid
rules would handicap Justice to the point he wouldn't be able to
work. The rules also keep Mrs. Justice, who wants to live at home,
from qualifying for some benefits she would get if she were
institutionalized.
   The couple plan to have a divorce ceremony at Trinity United
Methodist Church on Sunday and will be ask those present to bless
their divorce. Justice said the ceremony will help people
understand the way the two feel about the situation and dramatize
their criticism of the nation's health care system.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
