<DOCNO> AP890605-0048 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-05-89 1305EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-China-Martyrs     06-05 0551</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-China-Martyrs,0571</SECOND>
<HEAD>Beijing Residents Come Out to Honor Dead</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-China, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN BIERS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Chinese wearing black armbands of mourning are
streaming to hospitals and university campuses that have been
turned into makeshift memorial halls in honor of China's newest
martyrs.
   Hundreds, perhaps thousands of people are believed to have been
gunned down during the weekend by Chinese troops ordered to clear
Tiananmen Square of students demanding a freer society and less
corruption by their Communist rulers.
   Several dead were taken to Fuxing Hospital in Muxudi, site of
the massacre that began the siege of Beijing late Saturday night.
   By Sunday, the narrow alley leading to the hospital entrance was
jammed with people coming to view nearly two dozen victims whose
bodies were strewn in two hospital rooms for friends or family
members to identify.
   Thousands of mourners quietly filed through the rooms, quickly
placing handkerchiefs over their noses against the overpowering
stench of formaldehyde.
   Gaping bullet holes were clearly visible on most of the bodies.
Some faces were so disfigured that mourners had to pull back the
blood-soaked sheets covering the bodies to search for clues to make
a positive identification.
   Most of the victims were men in their 20s and 30s. One had
quickly been dressed in a gray suit and red tie, while the others
still had on the torn clothes of the night of the massacre.
   ``I want to cry,'' said a shaken woman as she peered into the
room from a dirty window.
   ``If we had guns, we'd get back at them,'' fumed a 40-year-old
worker after viewing the bodies.
   By Monday, many Beijing residents were wearing black armbands in
honor of the students and their supporters who died.
   The names of victims were read over the loudspeaker system at
Beijing University. Large banners and posters honoring the dead
went up at all major schools.
   ``A generation of brave heroes will go down in the annals of
history,'' read a black-draped banner across the main gate at
Beijing Normal University, one of the major centers of the
pro-democracy movement.
   Funeral music blared from loudspeakers in front of the Central
Academy of Minorities, where a black banner with the photograph of
a fallen student was strung.
   Across the street, an even larger black banner was put up above
the entrance to the Beijing Medical University Stomatological
Hospital. White flowers, a traditional Chinese sign of mourning,
were draped on trees and the main gate.
   Students at Political Science and Law University turned the
foyer of a classroom building into a memorial hall, where they
placed a bloodied and disfigured body of a dead classmate.
   A steady stream of students and residents filed through the
building's large front doors, which were flanked by huge banners
reading: ``An eternal injustice'' and ``Tragic beyond compare in
this human world.''
   The body lay on a table just to the left of the entrance. Huge
chunks of ice were scattered around the body to slow decomposition.
   ``I've come to grieve over the students who died,'' said a
middle-aged worker as he emerged from the building.
   After seeing the body, a trembling 24-year-old woman could only
berate the government that ordered the murderous attack.
   ``The Chinese government is crazy. They've gone way too far,''
she said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890605-0049 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-05-89 1332EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Hostages-Khomeini 1stLd-Writethru a0499 06-05 0712</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Hostages-Khomeini, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0499,0732</SECOND>
<HEAD>Khomeini's Death Dampens Hopes Of Hostage Release</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Inserts 1 graf after 10th pvs, ``The Bush...'' to UPDATE with
Bush calling for the release of the hostages. Pickup 11th graf, ``There
has...''</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Iran-Khomeini, Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FAROUK NASSAR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The political fallout from the death of
Iran's Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini is likely to prolong the
captivity of Western hostages held by pro-Iranian Shiite Moslem
extremists in Lebanon.
   Most of the 15 captives, including nine Americans, are held by
factions believed controlled by Hezbollah, or Party of God, Iran's
main Lebanese ally.
   Hezbollah's spiritual guide, Sheik Mohammed Hussein Fadlallah,
has tried in vain to keep his party out of the power struggle
between rival factions in Tehran for supremacy in the post-Khomeini
era.
   Hezbollah militants, backed by some 3,000 Iranian Revolutionary
Guards based in the ancient Roman city of Baalbek in eastern
Lebanon, have sided with Iran's hardliners led by Interior Minister
Ali Akbar Mohtashemi, according to Shiite sources who spoke on
condition of anonymity.
   Yet the party's political leadership in Beirut's southern slums,
Hezbollah's main power base, is aligned with Tehran's so-called
pragmatists, led by Parliament Speaker Hashemi Rafsanjani, the
sources said.
   Rafsanjani holds Hezbollah's purse strings.
   ``No one can tell how badly this split will reflect on the
hostages, but it's going to be bad,'' said one source close to
Fadlallah.
   ``There's going to be no way for quite a while to break the
deadlock shrouding their case,'' said the source.
   Much will depend on who emerges as the victor in the Tehran
power play. But that could take months.
   The Bush administration ``will have to sit tight and wait for
the dust of the Tehran power struggle to settle before it can make
any move on the hostages,'' the source said.
   President Bush said today in Washington he is unsure what will
happen in Iran now that Khomeini has died. But he added, ``There's
a way for Iran's relationship with the United States to improve and
that's for the release of the American hostages'' being held in
Lebanon.
   There has been no word on the hostages since the latest round of
fighting in Lebanon's 14-year-old civil war broke out March 8.
   Hezbollah and the rival pro-Syrian Amal militia has stayed out
of the battles, which pit Syrian against Christian forces. Many in
Beirut believe the Shiites' role on the sidelines has minimized the
risk that the hostages would be hit in shelling that has killed 360
people and wounded more than 1,400.
   Cardinal John O'Connor of New York made a three-day visit to
Lebanon two weeks ago to refocus attention on the hostages.
However, he left empty-handed after his repeated appeals to see the
American captives drew no reponse.
   A week before Khomeini's death, Beirut's Ash-Shiraa magazine
said the ``file of the hostages held in Lebanon is now in the hands
of Ahmad Khomeini,'' the ayatollah's son.
   Ash-Shiraa, which broke the story of the secret U.S.
arms-for-hostages deal that came to be known as the Iran-Contra
affair, also said Ahmad Khomeini recently summoned several
Hezbollah officials to discuss the hostages.
   The magazine said Khomeini's son is allied with Mohtashemi. It
suggested Iran's hardliners have taken charge of the hostage issue.
   Hezbollah publicly contends it has not been involved in the
waves of kidnapping that have swept Lebanon since Khomeini's brand
of fundamentalism swept Lebanon in 1983.
   But there is little doubt among Western and Lebanese
intelligence sources that all four factions holding most of the
American hostages operate under Hezbollah's wing and are controlled
by the party's militants.
   Among them is Islamic Jihad, or Islamic Holy War, which claimed
the abduction of American journalist Terry Anderson, the
longest-held hostage, and U.S. educator Thomas Sutherland.
   Anderson, chief Middle East correspondent for The Associated
Press, was kidnapped March 16, 1985. Sutherland was grabbed June 9
of that year.
   Anglican Church envoy Terry Waite is also believed to be held by
Islamic Jihad, although no claim has been made. He disappeared
after leaving a west Beirut hotel Jan. 20, 1987 for a meeting to
try to win the Americans' release.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   The writer, the AP's Beirut correspondent, has
covered the hostage story since it began.
</TEXT>
