<FIRST>r w AM-Pakistan-ArmsSale     06-05 0197</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Pakistan-Arms Sale,180</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pentagon Announces Arms Sale To Pakistan</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Pentagon notified Congress on Monday it
had approved sales of torpedoes and anti-aircraft missiles valued
at $68 million to Pakistan.
   The plans were announced the day Pakistan's Prime Minister
Benazir Bhutto was scheduled to arrive in the capital for talks
with President Bush, Secretary of State James A. Baker III and
congressional leaders.
   Pakistan has supported anti-Communist fighters battling the
Marxist government in neighboring Afghanistan, and has served as a
conduit for U.S. aid destined for the rebels.
   Assuming there are no objections on Capitol Hill, the Pentagon
said the Pakistani government would be allowed to purchase 64
Standard anti-aircraft missiles for deployment on some retired
frigates the United States has leased to Pakistan.
   That missile transaction is valued at $40 million, the Pentagon
said.
   Pakistan also will be allowed to purchase 64 Mk-46 torpedoes for
the same vessels in a deal valued at $28 million, the Pentagon
added.
   The U.S. Navy will oversee both transactions and will serve as
the prime contractor for the Standard missiles. The prime
contractor for the torpedoes will be Honeywell Inc. of Minneapolis,
Minn., the Pentagon said.
</TEXT>
