<FIRST>r a AM-Brites     06-05 0653</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Brites,0675</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bright &amp; Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TURLOCK, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A stowaway cat and her litter of kittens
born during a slow boat trip to Hawaii flew back home in style and
were met by a welcome home committee.
   When handlers opened a crate of cat chow in Hawaii, Sylvester
the cat and two surviving kittens emerged relatively unscathed,
although the new mommy was dehydrated, said Dick Rossow, customer
service manager at the Purina Mills plant in Turlock.
   During the sea voyage, Sylvester, who had been a mascot at the
Turlock plant 100 miles southeast of San Francisco, scratched open
a sack of food, Rossow said.
   The cat and kittens were flown back to the mainland courtesy of
Continental Airlines and were met at San Francisco International
Airport on Sunday by a limousine and a banner reading ``Welcome
Home, Sylvester and Family.''
   Rossow reported that company employees plan to adopt the kittens.
   ``The kittens are really cute, and they're all doing just
fine,'' he said. ``Sylvester's fine too but a little thin.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CAMBRIDGE, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Smoot as a unit of measure was
invented in 1958 at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology when
freshman fraternity pledges were ordered to measure the length of
Harvard Bridge using only chalk and the body of one Oliver Reed
Smoot Jr.
   The pranksters manhandled their fellow pledge end-to-end like a
ruler to measure the bridge. On the night of the fraternity prank,
the bridge was found to be 364.4 Smoots plus one ear.
   The bridge markings, maintained by Lambda Chi Alpha pledges for
30 years, threatened to become extinct when the 1891 bridge
recently was slated for a $16.5 million reconstruction.
   However, the Metropolitan District Commission and the Department
of Public Works decided the Smoot should stay when the sidewalk was
replaced.
   ``As a result of the Smoot withstanding the test of time, it has
become part of the folklore of the Harvard Bridge, and as such is
now under the protection of the MDC,'' declared the agency's chief
bridge engineer, David Lenhardt, at a re-Smooting ceremony Sunday.
   ``Out of the 14 pledges, I had the distinction of being the
shortest,'' explained Smoot, who is 5 feet 7 inches.
   ``And had the best name,'' said Peter S. Miller, who was in
charge of the chalk on that fateful night.
   Twice a year since, freshman pledges have faithfully
``re-Smooted'' the bridge that links MIT with Boston, marking each
10-Smoot length with a gash of paint on the sidewalk.
   The bridge's new sidewalk is scored at 5-foot 7-inch intervals
instead of the usual 6 feet, which will make it easier for future
pledges to repaint their Smoot marks, said Charles Madden, senior
vice president for Martin Continental Construction Co., the
contractor rebuilding the bridge.
   Smoot, now an executive with a trade group in Washington, D.C.,
lay down to have Miller chalk his measure on the new sidewalk.
Although the original deed was done in the dark of night,
interrupted once by a patrolling police car that sent the pledges
scurrying into the shrubs, the re-Smooting was punctuated with
flash bulbs and applause.
   Smoot and his son Stephen, MIT Class of '90, also posed in front
of a bronze commemorative plaque that was donated by Smoot's Class
of '62 at their 25th class reunion.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A freeway connection ramp that was
accidentally covered with Elmer's glue two weeks ago became a
slippery mess when Mother Nature added water.
   Officials closed the ramp connecting northbound state Route 99
to westbound U.S. 50 for about six hours Sunday after rain made the
road too slick for safe driving.
   Workers had tried to clean up the glue after it leaked from a
runaway trailer May 24, but apparently failed to get it all, the
California Highway Patrol said.
   The thunderstorm Sunday dropped .22 inches of rain on
Sacramento, nearly twice the average rainfall for all of June.
</TEXT>
