<FIRST>u w PM-US-China 4thLd-Writethru a0607 06-05 0889</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-US-China, 4th Ld-Writethru, a0607,940</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Announces Halt to Weapons Sales to China</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Inserts grafs 7-9, The State Department, with American students
in Beijing advised to leave campuses.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUSANNE M. SCHAFER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush said today he did not want ``to
see a total break'' with China in the wake of the government's
bloody repression of student demonstrations, but he announced a
series of sanctions in response to the crackdown.
   ``We cannot condone the violent attacks and cannot ignore the
consequences for our relationship with China,'' Bush said in a
statement in the White House briefing room.
   ``This is not the time for an emotional response,'' Bush said in
explaining to reporters why he had decided not to cut U.S.
diplomatic ties or to recall Ambassador James Lilley.
   ``I don't want to see a total break in this relationship and I
will not encourage a total break in this relationship,'' Bush told
reporters. ``When you see these kids struggling for democracy and
freedom this would be a bad time for the United States to
withdraw.''
   He renewed his call on the government in Beijing to avoid force
and to exercise retraint. To signal U.S. displeasure with the
crackdown, which left hundreds of students dead and hundreds of
others wounded, the president said he would suspend all military
sales and visits of Chinese military leaders.
   Also, Bush said, Chinese students wishing to extend their visits
here would get a sympathetic audience from U.S. officials. And, he
said, he was encouraging the Red Cross and other humanitarian
agencies to speed help to the injured.
   The State Department later announced all American students in
Beijing were being advised to leave the campuses and gather in
hotels because of the chaotic situation.
   Spokeswoman Margaret Tutwiler said there had been no threats
against the Americans.
   In other actions, the State Department issued a new travel
advisory, cautioning Americans not to visit the country, and
instituted a so-called ``warden system'' of asking those already in
China to make their presence known to U.S. diplomatic offices.
   Taking the long view, Bush said he was confident democracy will
triumph. ``The genie cannot be put back in the bottle again,'' he
said.
   Bush, who headed the U.S. liaison office in Beijing during the
opening days of modern U.S.-China ties, is slated to meet with
congressional leaders this afternoon.
   Although the topic is last week's NATO summit, White House
spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said he expected the group also would
discuss the Chinese crisis.
   Bush released a statement Saturday after Chinese troops opened
fire on demonstrators in Beijing, saying the administration
deplored the violent turn of events and urged ``restraint,
non-violence and dialogue.''
   On Sunday, Sen. Jesse Helms, R-N.C., and Rep. Stephen Solarz,
D-N.Y., from the far points of the liberal and conservative
spectrum, joined forces on CBS-TV's ``Face the Nation'' to demand
that Bush end military aid in retaliation for the bloody
suppression of pro-democracy demonstrators.
   Solarz said that unless Bush took a stronger stand on China,
``Congress will do it for him.''
   Solarz is chairman of the House Foreign Affairs Asian
subcommittee, and Helms is the ranking GOP member of the Senate
Foreign Relations Committee.
   Besides calling for the immediate return of Lilley, Solarz said
the United States should consider a suspension of trade in
high-technology items and a change in immigration regulations to
allow pro-democracy Chinese students to remain in America until it
is clear they won't be punished.
   ``I think it would be politically unacceptable and morally
unthinkable ... for us to continue to sell arms to a country that
is engaged in the wanton slaughter of its own people,'' Solarz said.
   Helms said he believed there was ``strong bipartisan support''
for the move.
   Sen. Alan Cranston, D-Calif., chairman of Foreign Relations
subcommittee on East Asian and Pacific affairs, also called for a
halt to all military assistance and cooperation with the People's
Republic of China, saying U.S.-Chinese relations had been dealt ``a
bloody blow.''
   But Sen. Richard Lugar, R-Ind., another member of the Senate
panel, advised a cautious approach.
   ``He ought to keep our ambassador there. ... We ought to
maintain our agreements (to supply aid),'' Lugar said on NBC-TV's
``Meet the Press.'' The senator said the U.S. leverage in the
matter is ``always very limited. There are some situations we
really cannot control.''
   Former Secretary of State Henry Kissinger, who helped forge the
first U.S. ties to China during President Nixon's term, also
advised that the president ``can't afford emotional outbursts'' in
the present situation.
   Appearing on ABC-TV's ``This Week With David Brinkley,''
Kissinger said he was ``appalled'' by the events in Beijing but
cautioned that the United States must be ``very careful'' about
considering cutting ties with the Chinese in order not to give the
Soviet Union ``a free ride'' in influence in Asia.
   The U.S.-Chinese relationship has blossomed on economic,
military and political fronts since formal diplomatic relations
were established in 1979.
   Since that time, the United States has sold more than $748
million in arms to China, most recently a $100 million deal in
which Beijing purchased six Chinook CH-47D helicopters manufactured
by Boeing Co.
   China, with U.S. approval, also reached a $245 million agreement
with Grumman Corp. in 1987 under which the U.S. company improved
the avionics of China's F-8 fighter jet.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
