<FIRST>r w AM-StampsPlanned     06-05 0381</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Stamps Planned,380</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ocean, Seashore to Be Featured on Stamps</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RANDOLPH E. SCHMID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Marine mammals, lighthouses and even beach
umbrellas will bring an oceanic theme to some of next year's
postage stamps, the U.S. Postal Service reports.
   While the full list of 1990 stamps and postal stationery has not
been completed, the agency has announced several of the issues
planned.
   The bicentennial of the U.S. Coast Guard will be marked by
issuance of a booklet of lighthouse stamps, the agency said.
   Featured will be the beacons at Admiralty Head, Wash.; Cape
Hatteras, N.C.; West Quoddy Head, Maine; American Shoals, Fla., and
Sandy Hook, N.J.
   A set of four stamps will feature marine mammals _ a walrus, sea
otter, bottlenose dolphin and killer whales.
   And turning to the shore, a colorful beach umbrella will appear
on a postcard-rate stamp intended for vacation use in writing home.
   Niagara Falls will make its appearance on a postal card in 1990,
while postal cards in the Historic Preservation series will feature
Constitution Hall of the Daughters of the American Revolution in
Washington and Stanford University.
   The national bicentennial stamps will continue in 1990 with a
stamp honoring the Supreme Court.
   And three statehood stamps will be issued, marking the
bicentennial of the last of the original colonies, Rhode Island,
and the centennials of Idaho and Wyoming.
   Two stamps will be issued offering views of America as it
appeared to early explorers.
   The Folk Art series will display five headdresses of Plains
Indians _ the Cheyenne, Comanche, Shoshone, Flathead and Assinboine.
   There will be a Love stamp, two Christmas stamps, and several
famous Americans will be honored with stamps in 1990. They include:
   _The late President Dwight D. Eisenhower, who will be honored on
the centennial of his birth.
   _George Caleb Bingham, a 19th century artist whose work featured
life along the Missouri River during the opening of the American
West.
   _Ida B. Wells, one of the founders of the National Association
for the Advancement of Colored People.
   _Luis Munoz Marin, first governor of Puerto Rico.
   _Claire Lee Chennault, founder of the Flying Tigers, a squadron
of American pilots who aided China in World War II.
   _Jesse Owens, a track and field legend.
   _Pulitzer Prize-winning poet Marianne Moore.
</TEXT>
