<FIRST>u i AM-Iraq-Iran     06-05 0492</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Iraq-Iran,0507</SECOND>
<HEAD>Iraq Calls For Peace With Iran, Rebels Switch Off Propaganda</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Khomeini, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SALAH NASRAWI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BAGHDAD, Iraq (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iraq on Monday called for a comprehensive
peace with Iran following the death of Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini.
   At the same time, Iranian rebels based in Iraq shut down their
propaganda machine in what diplomats suspect was an Iraqi move to
muzzle them in a goodwill gesture to Tehran.
   In Baghdad's first official reaction to Khomeini's death on
Saturday, the al-Thawra daily said: ``Iraq once again calls ... for
a comprehensive and just peace based on good neighborly relations
and non-interference in each other's internal affairs.''
   Iran and Iraq declared a cease-fire in their eight-year war in
August 1988, but have not concluded a peace treaty.
   The newspaper, mouthpiece of the ruling Baath Socialist Party,
said in an editorial that the ``death of Khomeini means the passing
of a vicious despot who spared no effort to fulfill his dream of
building a Persian empire at the expense of Iraq and other Arab
nations.''
   It warned that Khomeini's death will trigger a ``chapter of
struggle among different factions'' in Tehran.
   But it stressed that Iraq ``is looking forward to the new rulers
working for a peace settlement to the gulf war and new relations
based on non-interference.''
   The army-run al-Jomhuriya daily noted that Khomeini's death has
``opened the gates'' for peace between the two Persian Gulf
neighbors.
   Iraq has repeatedly charged that peace talks to formally end the
Persian Gulf war have deadlocked because political feuding in
Tehran has paralyzed Iran's decision-making.
   The editorials clearly reflected Baghdad's hopes that a more
flexible leadership will emerge in Tehran following Khomeini's
death.
   The Mujahedeen Khalq, or People's Holy Warriors, announced in
Baghdad that in the wake of Khomeini's death, they have halted
publication of their magazines, shut down their television station
in Iraq that beams propaganda into western Iran and called off
anti-Khomeini demonstrations in world capitals planned for June 20.
   The Mujahedeen noted, however, that their radio station, the
Voice of Mujahed, will continue broadcasting 16 hours a day.
   The group, the main Iranian opposition movement, said in a
statement the actions were ``part of efforts to make ever-greater
preparations to overthrow the remnants of Khomeini's regime.''
   But diplomats in Baghdad said it appeared that the shutdown was
more likely ordered by the Iraqi government to minimize Mujahedeen
propaganda and encourage Iranian leaders to respond to Iraq's peace
call.
   The diplomats said that was the only explanation for the
Mujahedeen action at a time when they had been expected to
intensify their propaganda to exploit the political uncertainty in
Iran.
   Mujahedeen officials said Sunday that their military arm, the
National Liberation Army of Iran, was ready to return to Iran to
overthrow the Tehran government ``at the appropriate time.''
   There was no indication that the army, with a strength estimated
at more than 20,000 fighters, was preparing military action.
</TEXT>
