<FIRST>u i AM-AIDS-Future     06-05 0588</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-AIDS-Future,0605</SECOND>
<HEAD>Grim New York AIDS Picture Foretells AIDS Future</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL RAEBURN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Editor</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MONTREAL (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   New York City has more reported AIDS cases than
the next four largest cities combined, and the epidemic is moving
swiftly through populations of drug abuses, minorities and the
poor, the city's top health official said Monday.
   ``The city's experience with the epidemic is in many ways a
foretelling of the future of AIDS for many other cities and
countries of the world,'' said New York's Commissioner of Health,
Dr. Stephen Joseph.
   ``An examination of this experience will yield, I suggest,
useful and important insights for application on the global
scale,'' he told the Fifth International Conference on AIDS.
   New York recently recorded its 20,000th case of the acquired
immune deficiency syndrome _ more than combined totals reported in
Los Angeles, San Francisco, Houston and Washington, D.C.
   More than 10,700 New Yorkers have died from the disease and
about 200,000 are infected, Joseph told the Montreal meeting.
   Sixty percent of New York's intravenous drug abusers already
have been infected with the human immunodeficiency virus (HIV) that
causes AIDS. In 1988, for the first time, the number of new cases
in drug abusers equaled the number of new cases in homosexual men.
   ``The increasing role of the drug abuser makes AIDS more a
disease of poor families,'' he said.
   In 1988, blacks and Hispanics made up close to 70 percent of New
Yorkers with AIDS.
   ``More and more, cocaine and crack are the engines driving the
spread of HIV infection among drug users and their sex partners,''
Joseph said.
   He elicited shouting and boos from activists when he said the
epidemic is reaching the point where it would be useful to begin
confidential reporting of the names of people who test positive and
to begin tracking their sexual contacts more actively.
   ``I think we will see a relative shift from anonymous to
confidential testing,'' he said, citing the increasing possibility
of preventing or at least forestalling illness in people infected
with the virus but otherwise healthy.
   In other reports, the National Gay Rights Advocates, a public
interest law firm in San Francisco, reported that Medicaid coverage
for AIDS patients varies widely from state to state.
   ``The brutal fact is that under the present Medicaid system, a
recipient's ability to survive the AIDS crisis often hinges upon
his or her state of residence,'' the group's report said.
   Dr. John Phair of Northwestern University Medical School in
Chicago reported the homosexual men who develop AIDS soonest are
those with the most sexual partners during their lifetimes. His
study also showed that most newly infected homosexual men will not
develop AIDS for more than 3{ years.
   Researchers at the University of Miami reported that of 122
homeless men and four homeless women who volunteered for AIDS
tests, 14, or 11 percent, were infected. ``The rate of HIV
infection among homeless persons voluntarily seeking testing is
relatively high,'' the researchers said.
   Joseph's speech was constantly interrupted by shouts and
chanting from AIDS activists, many from New York. They were
especially critical of his call for confidential reporting of the
names of infected people, fearing such information could be used to
discriminate against victims.
   Joseph estimated the cost of treating AIDS patients and others
infected will exceed $7 billion during the next five years.
   By the end of 1993, the city will need 4,000 to 5,000 hospital
beds daily to care for infected patients, he said. They now occupy
1,600 beds in New York.
</TEXT>
