<FIRST>r w AM-OceanIncineration     06-05 0283</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Ocean Incineration,260</SECOND>
<HEAD>EPA To `De-designate' Gulf Site Off Texas Coast</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Environmental Protection Agency has agreed
to abandon a site off the Texas Gulf Coast designated as the
country's only location for ocean incineration of hazardous wastes,
agency officials said Monday.
   Steps to revoke the designation of the site 220 miles east of
Brownsville hinge on resolution of a federal lawsuit in the
District of Columbia. The case challenges the EPA's decision not to
issue a permit to a Connecticut company, SeaBurn Inc., for
industrial waste incineration at sea.
   EPA argued in court it may not issue permits without
incineration regulations in place, and it has decided not to issue
those regulations. Also, the agency argued, congressional action
last year barring new ocean dumping of industrial waste also bars
incineration.
   Although the court in April sided with EPA's position, time has
not run out for SeaBurn Inc. to appeal the decision, said Tudor
Davies, director of EPA's office of Marine and Estuarine Protection.
   Once the court case is resolved, the EPA will officially propose
to revoke the site designation.
   ``EPA will begin proceedings to de-designate the site and the
conclusion of the judicial process in that case if the courts
ultimately uphold the agency's view of the law,'' said a May 24
letter to Sen. Phil Gramm, R-Texas, signed by William A.
Whittington, acting deputy assistant administrator of the EPA water
office.
   EPA decided in 1977 to formally designate the Gulf of Mexico
site in the event it eventually formulated regulations to permit
the burning of toxic wastes at sea. Early last year, the agency
decided not to proceed because of widespread concerns about the
impact of incineration.
</TEXT>
