<FIRST>r w AM-US-ChinaTrade     06-05 0380</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-China Trade,370</SECOND>
<HEAD>US-China Trade Jumps to Record $13.4 Billion</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Bush Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CARL HARTMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Trade between China and the United States
jumped by more than a third last year to a record $13.4 billion,
the U.S. International Trade Commission reported Monday.
   The increase marked a rise from the 1987 total of $9.7 billion.
In 1978, the figure surpassed the $1 billion mark for the first
time.
   ``A high rate of industrial growth in China during 1988 was
accompanied by record high inflation,'' the report noted.
   Now, like many other big U.S. trading partners, China sells much
more than it buys in this country. The U.S. deficit with China rose
to $3.4 billion from $2.8 billion the year before.
   Chinese sales to the United States rose by $2.2 billion to a
total of more than $8 billion. The increased Chinese exports were
largely manufactured goods, such as toys and games, but also items
that take more technical skill to produce: electrical, sound
recording and telecommunications equipment.
   U.S. exports were largely raw materials. They also rose, by $1.5
billion to more than $5 billion, with the increase led by
chemicals, wheat and softwood logs.
   The report noted that a new agreement with China on limiting
U.S. imports of textiles went into effect last year. There were
also new accords on sea transport and on launching American-built
communications satellites from Chinese soil. An agreement on
favorable U.S. tariff rates was renewed.
   U.S. trade with the Soviet Union showed a surplus of $2.2
billion, twice the 1987 figure, thanks to increased sales of corn,
wheat, soybeans and fertilizers. The Soviets increased their
exports by $155 million, largely because of increased fuel oil
shipments. Trade with the Soviets was up, but at $3.3 billion it
was less than one-fourth the China trade.
   The report called attention to improvement in U.S. trade
relations with the Soviets, including lifting of the embargo on
Soviet furs, extension of the agreemment on U.S. grain sales,
increased interest among U.S. companies in doing business in the
Soviet Union.
   Overall, U.S. trade with Communist countries reached a record
$19.2 billion in 1988, up from $13.8 billion the year before.
Increases were registered with all Eastern European countries with
the exception of Hungary.
</TEXT>
