<FIRST>r w AM-FCCVacancies     06-05 0349</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-FCC Vacancies,350</SECOND>
<HEAD>Commerce Department Official Reported Tapped for FCC Chairmanship</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAY ARNOLD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The White House has decided to nominate
Commerce Department official Alfred C. Sikes as the new chairman of
the Federal Communications Commission to replace Dennis R. Patrick,
according to a published report.
   The nomination of Sikes, who heads the department's National
Telecommunications and Information Administration, will be sent to
the Senate this week along with two names to fill three vacancies
on the five-member commission, Broadcasting Magazine said in its
June 5 issue.
   The magazine, quoting a source it did not identify, said Sikes,
a longtime friend and associate of Sen. John Danforth, R-Mo., won
out for the chairmanship over Sherrie Marshall, a Washington
attorney and former top aide to Patrick.
   Marshall will be nominated for one of the commissioner's seats,
along with Andrew C. Barrett, the magazine said. Barrett, a
Republican, is a member of the Illinois Commerce Commission.
   A call to Chase Untermeyer, director of the White House
personnel office, was not immediately returned Monday. Tom Cohen,
majority counsel to the Senate Commerce communications
subcommittee, said there had been no official word from the White
House as of Monday.
   A spokeswoman for Sikes, Nancy Mason, said rumors of his
nomination were still just that.
   Patrick, the deregulation advocate who battled continually with
Congress during his two years as FCC chairman, said in April he
would step down as soon as a successor was confirmed. He denied he
was being pushed out by the White House.
   The magazine said Sikes' nomination for the post had been
promoted by Danforth, the ranking Republican on the Commerce,
Science and Transportation Committee, which oversees the FCC.
   Sikes served as an assistant Missouri attorney general in 1969.
He managed Danforth's unsuccessful Senate campaign in 1970 and
served as director of the Missouri Department of Consumer Affairs
from 1974 to 1977. He also owned several Missouri radio stations.
   During his tenure at Commerce, the department endorsed
deregulation of the seven regional Bell telephone companies to
allow them into the information services areas.
