<FIRST>r a AM-LaRoucheAide     06-05 0220</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-LaRouche Aide,200</SECOND>
<HEAD>LaRouche Aide Sentenced to 10 Years in Prison</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LEESBURG, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An associate of Lyndon LaRouche Jr. was
sentenced Monday to 10 years in prison on securities violations
stemming from the political extremist's fund-raising activities.
   Rochelle Ascher, 38, of Towson, Md., had been convicted on
charges of selling an unregistered security with intent to defraud,
sale of a security by an unregistered agent with intent to defraud
and conspiracy, and six counts of securities fraud involving six
sales to four individuals.
   In a statement to Loudoun County Circuit Judge Carlton Penn, Ms.
Ascher maintained her innocence, and said the LaRouche
organization's ``entire purpose for existing is to combat
injustice, evil and poverty.''
   The judge declared: ``Not everything you have done is to the
benefit of the hungry and poor.''
   A jury on April 5 had called for her to be sentenced to 86 years
in prison, but Penn reduced it to 56 years and ordered that the
sentences be served in such a way that her term in prison would be
10 years.
   State officials had maintained that Ms. Ascher, 15 co-defendants
and five LaRouche organizations were part of a fund-raising
operation that allegedly bilked hundreds of people out of as much
as $30 million.
   The trial of other defendants has been moved to Roanoke.
</TEXT>
