<FILEID>AP-NR-06-05-89 2012EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Japan     06-05 0581</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan,0598</SECOND>
<HEAD>Uno Pledges Reform; Party Leaders Prepare to Quit Factions</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ERIC TALMADGE ^Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   New prime minister Sousuke Uno told lawmakers
Monday that political reform is at the top of his agenda. Governing
party leaders were reported ready to show their support by quitting
party factions.
   In a major policy speech, his first address to Parliament since
becoming prime minister on Saturday, Uno said restoring the
nation's trust in politics is his administration's most pressing
task.
   ``Restoring the people's faith in politics will strengthen the
base of peace and prosperity of our country and is indispensible to
strengthening our world image,'' he said in separate speeches to
both houses of Parliament.
   Uno took office more than a month after former Prime Minister
Noboru Takeshita announced he would resign to take responsibility
for the Recruit scandal, which has sent support for the governing
Liberal Democratic Party to all-time lows.
   ``Our cure must go to the very roots of this affliction so that
no similar disgrace will ever again occur,'' he said.
   Uno said his primary aims are to improve political ethics, draw
a clear line between the public and private use of political funds
and create an election system that does not require tremendous
funds.
   Fund-raising was a major factor in the scandal, named after the
Recruit Co., a publishing conglomerate that sold underpriced,
unlisted shares in its real estate subsidiary to more than 150
politicians, bureaucrats and businessmen in 1986.
   More than a dozen people have been arrested on bribery and other
charges. Two politicians were charged with accepting bribes, and
three Takeshita-appointed Cabinet ministers were forced to step
down due to Recruit ties.
   The reform campaign appeared to make progress Monday when
Liberal Democratic leaders and all Cabinet ministers said they
would resign from factions within the party, according to the Kyodo
News Service.
   Party factions, which provide formidable voting blocs, increase
the party's appetite for funds because faction leaders need money
to support the political activities of their followers.
   Uno, who has resigned from the faction formerly headed by
ex-Prime Minister Yasuhiro Nakasone, has vowed to abolish the
blocs, but he was careful to maintain a balance among factions when
naming his Cabinet.
   ``He may think he has demonstrated his will ... by placing
`political ideals and reform' at the top of his speech and with his
unprecedented wordiness on the subject,'' said an editorial in the
liberal Asahi Shimbun, Japan's second-largest newspaper. ``But the
speech sounded hollow.
   ``When you are caught in a whirlpool, it's difficult to see how
big it is,'' the editorial said, referring to the scandal.
   Analysts and opposition party members regard Uno, who served as
Takeshita's foreign minister from 1987, as a weak politician and
doubt he has the power to change Japan's money politics.
   ``He hasn't made amends for (the scandal) at all,'' said Iwao
Teramae, a Japan Communist Party legislator.
   On foreign policy, Uno said fulfilling Japan's international
responsibilities is ``indispensible.'' He indicated he will support
Takeshita's International Cooperation Initiative, which involves
peacemaking efforts, expanding overseas aid programs and
strengthening international exchange programs.
   Uno reaffirmed Japan's dual committment to the advanced
industrialized nations and to Asia, and he promised to support
continuing domestic demand-fueled growth as well as improve access
to Japan's markets.
   ``Now that Japan, which received the greatest benefit from the
postwar free trade system, has become strong economically, it is
not proper for her to express her own self-centered positions,'' he
said.
</TEXT>
