<SECOND>AM-US-PLO,240</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Schedules Another Talk Despite Infiltration</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States has scheduled another
meeting with the Palestine Liberation Organization despite reports
of an attempted infiltration of Israel by Palestinian militamen.
   Margaret Tutwiler, the State Department spokeswoman, said the
session would be on Thursday.
   In opening talks with the PLO last December the Reagan
administration gave public assurances to Israel that the dialogue
would be suspended if the PLO resorted to the terrorism that had
been renounced by Chairman Yasser Arafat.
   ``The series of infiltration attempts during the past week in
South Lebanon is very disturbing,'' Ms. Tutwiler said Monday. ``We
urge those responsible to refrain from incidents that can only
result in further violence and bloodshed.''
   The Israeli army said three infiltrators were intercepted within
the Israeli border early Sunday morning carrying Soviet-made
rockets and assault rifles and grenades. They were killed. An
Israeli Bedouin soldier also died in the clash.
   This was the third attempt by the Democratic Front for the
Liberation of Palestine to infiltrate Israel since Arafat's
statement cleared the way for talks with the United States, the
Israeli army said.
   The Palestinian group is part of the PLO and its deputy general
secretary is Abd al-Rabo, who heads the PLO delegation in the talks
with Robert Pelletreau Jr., the U.S. ambassador to Tunisia.
   Nine Arab guerrillas and one Israeli soldier have died in four
clashes over the past nine days.
