<SECOND>AM-Arms Sales,120</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pentagon Wants Arms Sales to Egypt, South Korea, Singapore</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Pentagon notified Congress on Monday it
had approved arms sales to South Korea, Egypt and Singapore.
   Assuming there are no congressional objections, the Pentagon
said it planned to sell South Korea 30 F-4E jet fighters along with
spare parts and support equipment in a deal valued at $246 million.
   The transaction with Egypt calls for helping that country modify
three of its Boeing 707 aircraft into KC-135 aerial refueling
tankers. The work is valued at $130 million.
   The deal with Singapore involves the sale of three
artillery-locating radar systems worth $31 million.
   The U.S. Air Force will oversee the first two transactions and
the U.S. Army will oversee the deal with Singapore, the Pentagon
added.
