<FIRST>r w AM-Bush-Cyprus     06-05 0280</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush-Cyprus,250</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Hopes Greek, Turkish Sides Will Build on U.N. Plan</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush said Monday he hopes a new
United Nations ``deconfrontation plan'' for Cyprus will be the
prelude to further progress in settling the dispute that has
divided the island for 15 years.
   Bush made the comment in a letter sent to leaders of Congress
advising them on progress toward a negotiated settlement of the
Cyprus question.
   Bush is required by law to submit a bimonthly report on Cyprus
to the speaker of the House and the chairman of the Senate Foreign
Relations Committee.
   Since the last report, Bush said, ``the U.N.'s deconfrontation
plan went into effect on May 17, greatly alleviating the
probability of incidents posed by the dangerously close proximity
of the two sides' military units in the Nicosia area.''
   He said the United States had worked hard for the U.N. effort
and added, ``we are hopeful that this achievement will prove the
prelude to further progress.''
   He said the Greek-Cypriot and Turkish-Cypriot sides have
continued efforts under the auspices of U.N. Secretary-General
Javier Perez de Cuellar ``to assemble the basic elements of a
settlement.''
   The subject has been discussed by top U.S., Greek and Turkish
officials in bilateral talks, he noted. Bush said he also discussed
it in a meeting with Turkish Prime Minister Turgut Ozal in Tokyo in
February.
   Bush also commended the appointment of Maj. Gen. Clive Milner of
Canada as commander of the U.N. Peacekeeping Force in Cyprus.
   Cyprus has been divided since Turkish troops invaded the
northern third of the island in 1974 in a move the Ankara
government said was to protect the Turkish Cypriot minority.
</TEXT>
