<FIRST>r w AM-Sealift     06-05 0325</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sealift,310</SECOND>
<HEAD>Witnesses Call for Greater Military Cargo Ability</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONNA CASSATA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The possibility of a conventional arms treaty
that would cut U.S. troops in Europe creates a greater need for
fast cargo ships to reinforce them in case of war, the chairman of
a Senate subcommittee said Monday.
   President Bush last week proposed ceilings on troops, tanks,
combat aircraft and attack helicopters, artillery and armored
personnel as part of a revised NATO response to Soviet leader
Mikhail S. Gorbachev's planned cuts in Warsaw Pact forces.
   ``If mutual reductions take place in Europe, American forces
will be withdrawn across the Atlantic while Soviet forces will
remain at the other end of the European rail network,'' Sen. Edward
Kennedy, D-Mass., chairman of the Senate Armed Services
subcommittee on projection forces and regional defense, said at a
hearing of the panel.
   ``In such an environment, a robust fast sealift program would be
a crucial element of continued conventional deterrence in Europe,''
Kennedy said.
   But the Massachusetts Democrat said the ``biggest gap to
reinforce NATO Europe is in fast sealift,'' a complaint that was
echoed by a series of former and present Pentagon officials.
   Witnesses told the Senate committee that U.S. sealift capability
has suffered as the nation's merchant marine has declined and
annual spending for research and development in shipbuilding has
decreased from $4.4 million to $500,000.
   ``Our long suit is people and technology and we're exploiting
neither in the world today,'' said Gen. Duane H. Cassidy,
commander-in-chief of the U.S. Transportation Command.
   Robert Costello, the Pentagon's former undersecretary for
acquisition, expressed dismay over Japan's 60-knot cargo ship, two
or three times as fast as conventional ships. ``We don't have
anything like that on the agenda,'' he said.
   Bush's proposal would reduce U.S. deployments in Europe from
about 330,000 troops to about 275,000. The president proposed the
same ceiling for Soviet deployments in eastern European countries
outside the Soviet Union.
</TEXT>
