<FIRST>r w AM-Fernandez-CIA     06-05 0421</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Fernandez-CIA,420</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former CIA Official Accused of Misleading Iran-Contra Probers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETE YOST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former CIA agent facing trial in the
Iran-Contra affair misled the Tower Commission and CIA
investigators in 19 instances, the government alleges in a newly
filed document.
   Joseph Fernandez, the CIA's former station chief in Costa Rica,
withheld from investigators early in 1987 details of his
involvement with Oliver North's secret Contra resupply network,
according to prosecutors.
   The three-page bill of particulars filed by the office of
independent counsel Lawrence Walsh is the most detailed summary to
date of allegedly misleading statements made by Fernandez.
   He faces a trial July 24 on charges of obstructing inquiries
into the Iran-Contra affair and making false statements. The 19
instances of allegedly misleading statements form the basis of the
government's two obstruction charges.
   Fernandez told congressional investigators in 1987 under a grant
of immunity from prosecution that he had been involved from the
inception in the planning of a secret airstrip in Costa Rica. He
also detailed extensive dealings with the Contras and a number of
contacts with North.
   Several months earlier, Fernandez told the CIA's office of
inspector general that he merely monitored the development of the
airstrip, according to the bill of particulars.
   Fernandez told the Tower Commission in January 1987 he had only
occasional conversations with North before September 1986,
according to the document.
   It was filed Friday in U.S. District Court in Alexandria, Va.,
and a copy was made available Monday by the independent counsel's
office in Washington.
   Fernandez also told the Tower Commission that he had never
communicated with Richard Secord, whom North had enlisted to run
arms to the Contras.
   In his subsequent testimony to Congress in a deposition,
Fernandez said he had met with Secord in Washington and discussed
the secret Costa Rican airstrip. The airstrip was to be used to
help resupply the Contras battling the leftist government of
Nicaragua.
   Fernandez also said in January 1987 that he hadn't had any
contact with Felix Rodriguez since 1971. He later told Congress
that he spoke with Rodriguez by phone during the period of the
secret Contra resupply operation.
   North brought Rodriguez into the resupply operation in September
1985.
   Rodriguez is a long-time acquaintance of Donald Gregg, who was
George Bush's national security adviser when he was vice president.
Bush has nominated Gregg to be U.S. ambassador to South Korea, but
the nomination is mired in the Senate over questions about Gregg's
role in the Iran-Contra affair.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
