<HEAD>Fire Cuts Power in Downtown Washington</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hundreds of downtown office workers were sent
home Monday after an early morning fire shut down six electrical
feeder cables.
   An estimated 150 offices were closed, ranging from small
businesses with a few employees to entire buildings with thousands
of workers, according to Potomac Electric Power Co. spokesman
Eileen Griffin.
   Traffic police at intersections without stoplights could not
prevent rush-hour snarls in the afternoon.
   Dave Masters, Pepco's on-site supervisor, said up to 60 major
buildings were affected.
   ``Right now we expect to have power back sometime between
midnight and 4 a.m. (Tuesday),'' said Pepco spokesman Tom Welle.
``People can come back to work, but we're asking them to try to
conserve some power.''
   The cause of the fire was not determined, said Welle. He said
the blaze started in a secondary cable that carries 600 volts.
   The underground fire in the six, 13,200-volt lines and resulting
explosion blew manhole covers into the air, authorities said.
   No injuries were reported, but workers had to replace 1,000 feet
of cable, tedious job.
   Among those apparently affected by the outage were the CBS News
Washington bureau, MCI Communications corporate offices and the
Federal Communications Commission.
</TEXT>
