<SECOND>AM-Cambodia,0371</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pol Pot Asks to Resign from Last Official Post</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pol Pot, whose Khmer Rouge regime was
blamed for the deaths of more than a million Cambodians, has asked
to resign from his last official post, a radio report said Monday.
   Some Western diplomats expressed doubt that the Cambodian
guerrilla leader was calling it quits.
   The Khmer Rouge's clandestine Voice of Democratic Kampuchea
radio station said Sunday that Pol Pot, in a letter dated March 4,
had asked to step down as head of the guerrilla group's High
Institute for National Defense.
   The Khmer Rouge defeated Cambodia's U.S.-backed government in
April 1975. His regime is blamed for the deaths of more than a
million Cambodians who were killed in purges or who perished during
a radical campaign to abandon the cities and establish a rural,
communist society.
   Vietnam invaded Cambodia in late 1978, ousted the Khmer Rouge
and established another communist government. The Khmer Rouge then
returned to guerrilla warfare.
   The broadcast said Pol Pot addressed the letter to Khieu
Samphan, who became the Khmer Rouge chairman in 1985 after Pol Pot
announced he had resigned from all major military and political
posts.
   It said Pol Pot asked for a decision on his request by the
beginning of June. No reason was given for the request, but the
broadcast said Pol Pot asked to remain with the research institute
``until all the Hanoi (Vietnamese) aggressors are driven out of
Cambodia. From then on I will cease all my activities in the organs
of the future state of Cambodia.''
   One Western diplomat, speaking on condition of anonymity, said,
``I certainly wouldn't take it at face value that he is no longer
involved in the leadership of the Khmer Rouge.
   ``They are moving towards negotiations, and Pol Pot is the No. 1
unacceptable figure.''
   The Vietnamese-installed government and an opposition coalition
of the Khmer Rouge, supporters of Prince Norodom Sihanouk and
non-communist guerrillas have held negotiations on a peace
settlement and new government.
   All parties except the Khmer Rouge have insisted that Pol Pot
and other leaders of his regime be removed from any position of
power.
</TEXT>
