<FILEID>AP-NR-06-05-89 2039EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-Oats-Canada     06-05 0182</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Oats-Canada,180</SECOND>
<HEAD>Canada Opens Door to American Oats _ No License Required</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   American oats and oat products can be sold to
Canada without import licenses because the U.S. price support level
is below Canada's, the two countries announced Monday.
   The U.S. support level for oats is 8.74 percent, while in Canada
it is 11.09 percent, the Agriculture Department said.
   Under the free trade agreement signed between the two countries
last year, Canada agreed to remove import licensing requirements if
U.S. support levels were equal to or below those of Canada.
   Supports are government subsidies that put a floor under prices.
The U.S. mechanism for doing this is a price-support loan program
under which farmers use crops as collateral and are free to forfeit
and keep the money if that nets them a greater return than selling
on the market.
   Import licenses will be required for wheat and barley. The
support comparisons for those commodities are wheat, 61.62 percent
in the United States and 46.28 percent in Canada; barley, 72.49
percent in the United States and 50.23 in Canada.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890605-0085 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-05-89 2040EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-Kemp-Miami     06-05 0476</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Kemp-Miami,0491</SECOND>
<HEAD>HUD Secretary Announces Subsidies To Reward Urban Development Efforts</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRIAN MURPHY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Using Miami's bleak Overtown neighborhood as a
backdrop, Housing Secretary Jack Kemp announced a program Monday to
use federal housing subsidies to reward cities with promising
anti-poverty programs.
   Operation Bootstrap, dedicated to the late U.S. Rep. Claude
Pepper, will allocate about 3,000 Section 8 housing subsidy
certificates among areas with innovative projects such as job
training, inner-city business development and public-private
partnerships, said the secretary of Housing and Urban Development.
   Section 8 recipients receive federal subsidies for 70 percent of
their rent. There are presently 2.9 million people in the
15-year-old Section 8 program, said HUD spokesman Bill Galvin in
Washington.
   Under the new program, each of the 3,000 certificates would
supply funding for one person. Kemp did not say how much the
certificates were worth.
   Kemp, a former conservative Republican congressman from Buffalo,
N.Y., also told Dade County business leaders that he encourages tax
reforms to eliminate capital gains taxes for companies opening or
expanding in some of the nation's most impoverished areas.
   ``We have to bring the entrepreneurial spirit, the spirit of
risk-taking, into the inner-city, places like Overtown or the South
Bronx or East LA,'' said Kemp, referring to sections of New York
City and Los Angeles.
   Kemp said the idea for Operation Bootstrap was launched earlier
this year by Pepper, the Miami Democrat who died of cancer last
week at the age of 88. Pepper's funeral and burial were held Monday
in Tallahassee.
   The program is intended to help defray housing costs for
low-income people seeking jobs and, eventually, home ownership,
said Kemp.
   ``I don't think you can talk about jobs without housing, and I
don't think you can talk about housing without jobs,'' said Kemp.
   Kemp said HUD officials will review proposals submitted by
cities and distribution of the Section 8 certificates will begin in
September.
   Kemp said sections of the nation with high refugee and immigrant
populations, such as South Florida and Southern California, are a
priority for Bush Administration funds.
   ``How can we tell China or the Soviet Union or African or Latin
nations that democracy works if it's not working in Overtown and
Liberty City ... in Bedford-Stuyvesant and Watts,'' said Kemp, who
visited Overtown following three days of rioting last January.
   Earlier Monday, Kemp visited the 31-year-old Camillus House
homeless shelter in downtown Miami and pledged to seek federal
grants for the privately funded, 70-bed facility.
   Kemp visited the shelter at the invitation of Norman Braman, a
Miami businessman and owner of the Philadelphia Eagles NFL football
team.
   With reports circulating that outgoing NFL Commissioner Pete
Rozelle was considering Kemp as a possible successor, the former
quarterback said he is content with his HUD post, but would not
reject an NFL offer before it is made.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
