<FILEID>AP-NR-06-05-89 2049EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Israel-Scrolls     06-05 0271</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Israel-Scrolls,0280</SECOND>
<HEAD>Improper Prayer Scrolls Blamed for Deaths</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A mayor who feared that divine retribution
killed three city managers in less than a month has ordered dozens
of improper prayer scrolls removed from doorjambs in the city hall,
a spokesman said Monday.
   Mayor Maxim Levy of Lod, near Tel Aviv, became suspicious of the
mezuzahs, or parchment scrolls traditionally attached to doorjambs,
after the third death May 18, spokesman Jack Sheetrit said.
   All three deaths were from natural causes, doctors said, and
none of the circumstances were unusual.
   According to Talmudic writings, affixing a mezuzah helps protect
believers from harm.
   Levy asked ultra-Orthodox rabbis to examine the building's 111
scrolls and they discovered faults in 87 that made them improper,
Sheetrit told The Associated Press.
   ``There were all kinds of problems. Some ... were only
photocopies, and in others the words of the prayer were wrong,'' he
said.
   ``The mayor is religious and he believes in the power of the
mezuzah. So he thought the first thing he had to do'' was change
them.
   According to Jewish law, a mezuzah must contain certain verses
from the book of Deuteronomy written in square Hebrew characters on
a piece of parchment made from the skin of a clean animal. The word
``Almighty'' must be written on the back of the parchment.
   The rolled parchment is inserted in a small case, which is
affixed to the right doorjamb.
   Sheetrit said Levy had changed the mezuzahs at the entrance to
the city hall and on the doorjamb of his office, and had ordered
new scrolls for the rest of the building.
</TEXT>
