<FIRST>r w AM-Bush-Nominations 1stLd-Writethru   06-05 0312</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush-Nominations, 1st Ld - Writethru,a0709,310</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush to Nominate Education, Interior, Diplomatic Aides</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Adds 2 grafs on Rodman, Tomsen</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush said Monday he will nominate
Edward C. Stringer, a Pillsbury Co. executive, to be general
counsel of the Department of Education.
   Stringer, a Minneapolis resident, has been general counsel of
Pillsbury since 1980. He is also the company's executive vice
president and chief administrative officer.
   The White House said Bush also plans to nominate Constance
Bastine Harriman as assistant secretary of the interior for fish
and wildlife.
   An attorney, she is a former associate solicitor for energy and
resources at the Interior Department. She has been in private
practice with the firm of Steptoe and Johnson in the capital since
1987. She lives in Bethesda, Md.
   Stringer is a 1957 graduate of Amherst College and a 1960
graduate of the University of Minnesota Law School.
   Harriman graduated from Stanford in 1970 and from the University
of California law school in 1980.
   Bush also named Everett Ellis Briggs, the U.S. ambassador to
Honduras since 1986, as a special assistant for national security
affairs. Briggs will be senior director of the National Security
Council for Latin America and the Caribbean.
   Briggs was ambassador to Panama from 1982 to 1986.
   Bush also named two other special assistants for national
security affairs:
   _Arnold Kanter, a RAND Corp. senior staff member and former
State Department official who will be senior director for defense
policy and arms control.
   _Deane E. Hoffman, a career intelligence officer who will be
senior director of international economic affairs.
   _Peter W. Rodman, a former Henry Kissinger assistant, as
counselor for the National Security Council.
   The White House said Bush also has accorded the personal rank of
ambassador to Peter Tomsen in his capacity as special envoy to the
Afghan resistance. Tomsen is a career foreign service officer.
</TEXT>
