<FIRST>r w AM-Bush-ElephantIvory     06-05 0256</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush-Elephant Ivory,240</SECOND>
<HEAD>Total Ban on Imports Imposed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush, in an announcement timed to
mark World Environment Day, said Monday the United States is
banning the import of elephant ivory from all countries.
   ``We do this out of mounting concern for the rapid decline of
the wild elephant, one of nature's most majestic creatures,'' he
said.
   ``If their populations continue to dimish at current rates, the
wild elephant will soon be lost from this earth. We urge the
nations of the world to join us in this ban.''
   Bush said people around the world have become more and more
concerned about such environmental problems as global warming,
depletion of the ozone layer, and mounting waste disposal problems.
   But, Bush said, ``I am optimistic about the future.''
   The United States has made ``remarkable progress in cleaning up
our air and water. We have shown what we can do when the will is
there and we work together,'' the president said.
   ``If we can probe the depths of space and engineer the genetic
building blocks of life, we can surely protect the quality of our
environment,'' he said.
   The United States already bans the import of ivory outside the
current system of international regulation. Last month the Bush
administration said it would press for a complete end to
international trade in ivory.
   The population of the African elephant today is estimated as low
as 400,000, compared with 1.5 million in 1978, because of the
inroads of poachers killing the animals for their ivory.
</TEXT>
