<FIRST>r i AM-Egypt-Drugs     06-05 0260</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Egypt-Drugs,0267</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge Sentences 19 Foreigners to Death for Drug Smuggling</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SUEZ, Egypt (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge in this port city sentenced an
American and 18 other foreigners to death after they were convicted
of attempting to smuggle more than six tons of illegal narcotics
into Egypt.
   Six of the accused, including the U.S. man, are still at large
and were sentenced in absentia at Sunday's court session.
   The 13 imprisoned defendants were arrested in July in Suez
aboard the freighter Reef Star, registered in St. Vincent and the
Grenadines. They are from Sudan, Bangladesh, India, Pakistan and
Kenya.
   The six men sentenced in absentia were identified as Kayed
Mohammed Hussein Berro, a Lebanese-born naturalized U.S. citizen;
Berro's Lebanese father; three Palestinians and an Israeli. Berro's
hometown was not known.
   Prosecutors said that in the raid on the Reef Star police seized
4.1 tons of opium, 1.8 tons of hashish and more than 600 pounds of
heroin hidden in butane gas bottles. They said the narcotics were
being smuggled into Suez for sale in Egypt and transfer to other
countries.
   Judge Mohammed Hafez Tawfik convicted the 19 of drug smuggling
in a verdict announced May 18 and sent their records to Egypt's
highest Moslem cleric, the mufti. Egyptian law requires an opinion
from the mufti in cases where the death sentence is decreed but the
specific crime does not violate Islamic tenets.
   The mufti's decision is not binding, but the theologian approved
the sentences for the 19, and Tawfik issued them Sunday.
   The defendants have 40 days to appeal.
</TEXT>
