<FIRST>r i AM-CentralAmerica     06-05 0156</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Central America,0159</SECOND>
<HEAD>Central American Presidents to Hold Another Peace Summit in July</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TEGUCIGALPA, Honduras (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Jose Azcona Hoyo
announced Monday he and four other Central American chief
executives will meet in July to pursue a regional peace plan.
   In an interview on radio station HRN he said he and the
presidents of El Salvador, Costa Rica, Nicaragua and Guatemala will
meet July 7-9 at a Honduran beach resort _ either Tela or Roatan.
   The five presidents have held several summit conferences under a
peace plan proposed in 1987 by Costa Rican President Oscar Arias.
   Arias won the Nobel Peace Prize for the plan designed to
negotiate an end to the war in Nicaragua between the Sandinista
government and U.S.-backed rebels and the fighting between
left-wing insurgents and government forces in El Salvador and
Guatemala.
   The initiative has achieved a frail cease-fire in Nicaragua, but
the conflicts continue in El Salvador and Guatemala.
