<FIRST>r w AM-GrainSale     06-05 0169</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Grain Sale,160</SECOND>
<HEAD>1.8 Million Ton Wheat Sale to China Announced</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   China has purchased another 1.8 million metric
tons of U.S. wheat, the Agriculture Department announced Monday.
   The announcement came as President Bush was halting military
sales to China over that government's bloody crackdown against
pro-democracy demonstrators in Beijing's Tiananmen Square.
   Bush said, however, he wants regular trade between the two
countries to continue without interruption. He said economic
sanctions to protest the use of force to dispel the demonstrators
could ``hurt the Chinese people.''
   The latest sale of soft red winter wheat brought to 2.65 million
metric tons of the commodity that the Chinese have purchased for
delivery in the marketing year that began June 1.
   Most of it has been purchased over the last two weeks.
   A metric ton is about 2,205 pound and equals 36.7 bushels of
wheat or 39.4 bushels of corn.
   In the marketing year that ended May 31, exporters sold 8.3
million metric tons of U.S. grain to China.
</TEXT>
