<FILEID>AP-NR-06-05-89 2136EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-SwindallTrial     06-05 0487</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Swindall Trial,0503</SECOND>
<HEAD>Witness Says Former Congressman Knew Money Laundering Was Involved</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BYRD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The man who introduced Pat Swindall to an
undercover agent testified Monday that the former congressman knew
money laundering was involved in an $850,000 loan deal involving
the three men.
   ``Mr. Swindall told me he didn't give a damn where the money
came from,'' Charles LeChasney said during Swindall's federal
perjury trial.
   Swindall is accused of lying to a federal grand jury about his
1987 dealings with LeChasney, a political associate, and Internal
Revenue Service agent Mike Mullaney, who was posing as money broker
``Mike Martinez.''
   Swindall was seeking money to finish building his suburban
Atlanta home.
   In his second day on the stand, LeChasney said that on Sept. 14,
1987, when the deal was discussed in Swindall's presence, the
defendant indicated he understood money laundering was involved.
   The prosecution witness said Swindall told him the deal was a
good way for Mullaney and his clients, purportedly drug kingpins,
``to wash the money.''
   LeChasney said he discussed with Swindall how he would handle
the $850,000 ``in such a way that we would not be caught''
violating money-laundering laws.
   LeChasney, an admitted con man who has been convicted of money
laundering, testified that he became concerned after Mullaney
suggested Swindall meet with his boss, ``Raul,'' another undercover
agent.
   The witness said he urged Swindall to ``tell Mike he could not
launder his money.'' Swindall followed that advice on Sept. 26,
1987, when the deal fell through, LeChasney said.
   The day before, Swindall signed papers arranging for a $150,000
advance on the $850,000 loan from LeChasney's Gulf Coast Mortgage
Corp., according to documents entered as evidence Monday.
   Swindall's attorney has called the $150,000 a separate loan, but
LeChasney said Monday the terms were those outlined in his
discussions with Swindall and Mullaney.
   The $150,000 check Swindall received from LeChasney's attorney
was backed by a personal check from LeChasney to the lawyer, with
the understanding that Mullaney would make the check good, the
witness said.
   Swindall attorney Richard Hendrix began cross-examining
LeChasney late Monday afternoon, attacking the witness's history of
fraud and deceit.
   LeChasney said he has never lied under oath in court, but
conceded he was an accomplished liar in attempts to influence
others. He said he told Mullaney and a government informant that he
had extensive political and diplomatic connections and was
executive producer of the hit films ``Urban Cowboy'' and
``Romancing the Stone,'' among other falsehoods.
   Swindall's attorneys have indicated they will seek to prove
LeChasney is a ``sociopathic'' liar who deceived the government
into thinking Swindall was a crook and tricked the congressman into
thinking the money deal was OK.
   Swindall, a two-term Republican, lost his 4th Congressional
District seat to Democrat Ben Jones last November.
   If convicted of all 10 counts against him, Swindall faces a
maximum sentence of 50 years in prison.
</TEXT>
