<FILEID>AP-NR-06-05-89 2140EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Europe-Space     06-05 0207</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Europe-Space,0213</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ariane Rocket Places Two Satellites in Orbit</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KOUROU, French Guiana (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Ariane 4 rocket lifted off
flawlessly from the European Space Agency's launch center Monday
and placed Japanese and West German telecommunications satellites
into orbit.
   Agency officials called the launch from this French territory in
South America a complete success.
   They said the rocket, a 44L model that is the largest in the
Ariane series, left the launch pad at 7:36 p.m. (6:36 p.m. EDT)
with the West German post office's DFS Kopernikus 1 and the
Superbird A satellite owned by Space Communications Corporation, a
subsidiary of Japan's Mitsubishi.
   It was the 31st launch of the Ariane series and the fourth this
year.
   It had been scheduled for May 26 but was postponed during the
final countdown because of insufficient liquid hydrogen pressure in
the third stage.
   Officials reported no problems Monday, and the rocket went into
orbit 17 minutes and 53 seconds after liftoff. Seven minutes and 13
seconds later both satellites were released into geostationary
orbit, they said.
   It was the 13th consecutive successful launch for Ariane. There
have been four failures since the first launch on Dec. 24, 1979,
and three were blamed on problems with the third stage.
</TEXT>
