<DOCNO> AP890605-0105 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-05-89 2204EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-PSACrash     06-05 0520</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-PSA Crash,0533</SECOND>
<HEAD> Failed Attempt to Regain Job Preceded Revenge-Suicide Flight</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An airline ticket agent pleaded to be
reinstated in his job just hours before he opened fire aboard an
airliner carrying the boss who fired him, killing all 43 aboard, an
FBI agent testified Monday.
   Special Agent Alan Hawkins told a Superior Court jury that
former USAir ticket agent David A. Burke confessed to his
supervisor that he had a drug and alcohol problem but wanted the
airline to rehire him.
   But supervisor Raymond Thomson refused to rehire Burke because
of theft allegations, Hawkins said. Shortly thereafter, the two
boarded Pacific Southwest Airlines Flight 1771 in Los Angeles on
Dec. 7, 1987, bound for San Francisco.
   Investigators believe that after the plane took off, Burke shot
Thomson with a handgun he had smuggled on board. Burke then stormed
the cockpit, shot the pilot and co-pilot, and their slumping bodies
sent the plane into a steep, fatal dive.
   The testimony came in the second week of a multimillion-dollar
lawsuit focusing on how Burke was able to pass through a security
checkpoint armed with a .44-caliber Magnum.
   The owner of the ranch where the plane went down and the
survivors of seven passengers and two crew members claim the
security measures were faulty. The defendants _ PSA, USAir, the
city's Department of Airports and Ogden Allied Security Co. _ hold
Burke alone responsible and have filed a countersuit.
   Ronald Wecht, an attorney for the plaintiffs, said Burke also
bought a $350,000 insurance policy from a vending machine before
boarding the flight.
   Burke, a 16-year employee, approached the PSA passenger
screening station at Los Angeles International Airport wearing an
invalid badge, said Gerald Sterns, a member of the legal team
representing plaintiffs in 35 cases consolidated for the trial.
   Sterns said security should have checked to see whether the
badge Burke was wearing was current. And since Burke was not in
uniform, he should have been searched.
   ``But none of this was done,'' Sterns said. ``She just says,
`Have a nice day.' And he replies, `I'll have a very nice day.'''
   ``The next thing we know, he turns up, back on the public side
of the checkpoint,'' Sterns said.
   That's when Burke talked to his former boss, Thomson, pleading
for his old job as a USAir ticket agent. Thomson, 48, a station
manager for USAir, the company that bought PSA, took six pages of
notes during the 30-minute meeting with Burke.
   After his unsuccessful attempt to regain his former post, the
35-year-old Burke stopped by a PSA passenger counter, where he
bought a ticket, according to court documents.
   Investigators believe that about 30 minutes after the plane took
off, Burke handed Thomson a note, scribbled on an airsickness bag.
The note said: ``Hi, Ray. I think it's sort of ironical that we
ended up like this. I asked for some leniency for my family.
Remember? Well, I got none and you'll get none.''
   All on board were killed as the four-engine plane slammed nose
first mph into the rugged coastal backcountry of San Luis Obispo
County.
</TEXT>
