<DOCNO> AP890605-0106 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-05-89 2227EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-China-WorldReaction 2ndLd-Writethru a0735 06-05 1130</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-China-World Reaction, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0735,1164</SECOND>
<HEAD>Religious, Political Leaders Condemn Massacre</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 4 grafs UPDATING with Canadian action. Picks up 6th
graf, `Delegations and...' DELETING 32d graf, `Canadian legislators...'
which superseded. SUB final graf, `In Mexico...' with 2 grafs UPDATING
with embassy pelted</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-China, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ERIC TALMADGE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Political and religious leaders of the world Monday
condemned the massacre of pro-democracy demonstrators in Beijing,
and hundreds of thousands of protesters swarmed to rallies to
denounce the bloodshed.
   In Ottawa, External Affairs Minister Joe Clark told Parliament
during an emergency debate on China that Canadians are being
advised to leave Beijing at once and that Canada has arranged for
aircraft to be available if the Beijing airport closes. Clark was
given a standing ovation when he proposed an all-party resolution
condemning the ``excessive and indiscriminate'' violence used
against the demonstrators.
   Switzerland, which rarely criticizes foreign governments,
summoned the Chinese ambassador to protest the force used by troops
trying to quell the student-led popular uprising.
   President Bush said in Washington he will suspend all military
sales to China and visits of Chinese military leaders, but will not
cut diplomatic ties.
   Delegations and dignitaries from Australia, Denmark, Norway,
Sweden and the European Economic Community canceled planned trips
to China. Protest rallies included ones throughout West Germany, in
Oslo and across from U.N. headquarters in New York.
   Students from China and Portuguese-administered Macao protested
in Lisbon and Coimbra, Portugal, but Portugal said there were no
plans to suspend a 1986 accord to return Macao to China in 1999,
state RTP television reported.
   Sunday's killing of hundreds of unarmed students and residents
in Beijing sent strong shock waves through neighboring Hong Kong
and Taiwan, where sympathizers staged huge rallies.
   President Lee Teng-hui said the Chinese military's attacks will
bring down the Beijing government, Taiwan's rival since the 1949
communist revolution drove the Nationalist Chinese from the
mainland.
   A similar sentiment came from President Francois Mitterrand of
France, who said: ``A regime which is reduced to firing on its
youth to survive, when the youth it has educated rises up in the
name of freedom, has no future.''
   Hong Kong, a British colony and bustling center of capitalism,
is to revert to Chinese rule in 1997. The violence left its 5.7
million people fearing for their future.
   Many in Hong Kong wept as they watched televised reports of
Sunday's assaults. Up to 1 million residents on Sunday staged the
colony's largest march in solidarity with Beijing demonstrators.
   ``I do not think the British people would accept the idea that
Hong Kong should be handed over to a bunch of medieval murderers,''
said legislator Anthony Beaumont-Dark of Prime Minister Margaret
Thatcher's Conservative Party.
   British Foreign Secretary Sir Geoffrey Howe summoned a senior
Chinese diplomat to register Britain's concern about the bloody
repression. But he said Hong Kong's future remains ``inextricably
bound ... with mainland China.''
   Soviet television broadcast dramatic footage of clashes between
Chinese troops and protesters, but officials made no comment,
apparently silenced by the fledgling friendship growing from last
month's historic summit between Soviet President Mikhail S.
Gorbachev and Chinese leaders.
   ``We have been taught by our own history that truth does not
come from the barrel of a rifle, nor do solutions,'' the Hungarian
Communist Party daily Nepszabadsag said.
   A spokesman for Yugoslavia's Foreign Ministry said Yugoslavs
feel ``grief for the human casualties.''
   Tiny, orthodox-communist Albania's official news agency referred
to Chinese troops ``brutally oppressing'' students.
   Czechoslovak media quoted casualty figures reported in Western
media, while East Germany stressed Chinese press releases.
   The Foreign Ministry of conservative El Salvador said, ``It is
one more example that the Marxist-Leninist system is contrary to
basic rights of citizens.''
   Lonely voices of support for China came from Nicaragua and in an
official Vietnamese radio broadcast, which said troops in Beijing
were attacked by hooligans and ruffians and were justified in
fighting back.
   Nicaragua's official Barricada newspaper quoted Chinese leaders'
claims that the order to attack avoided chaos and greater bloodshed.
   In West Germany, Chancellor Helmut Kohl angrily denounced the
``barbaric use of force,'' and Labor Minister Norbert Bluem said a
special session of the United Nations should be convened on the
assault.
   But U.N. Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar cautioned
there is little the world body can do.
   ``The secretary-general is greatly saddened that it was felt
necessary to resort to force in Beijing,'' spokesman Francois
Giuliani said. ``The secretary-general is most mindful of the
(U.N.) charter's requirement that the United Nations abstain from
intervention in regard to matters that are essentially within the
domestic jurisdiction of states.''
   For the same reason, the United Nations has taken no action on
China's crackdown on Tibetan activists.
   The Dalai Lama, Tibet's exiled spiritual leader, said he was
deeply saddened by the loss of lives.
   In London, Amnesty International called on all governments to
condemn the ``deliberate killing'' and to press China's government
to halt the violence.
   ``It is important for governments carrying out human rights
violations to be made aware of the revulsion such actions cause to
ordinary men and women in every part of the globe,'' the human
rights organization said.
   The World Council of Churches on Monday expressed ``shock and
profound consternation'' on behalf of its 300 churches representing
400 million non-Roman Catholic Christians.
   Pope John Paul II, on a tour of Scandinavia, said, ``As
Christians, we hope that these deaths may serve to bring about new
life in that great and beloved country.''
   President Corazon Aquino of the Philippines, swept to power by a
popular uprising that ousted President Ferdinand Marcos in 1986,
said she was ``very sad about the violent turn of events.''
   Opposition leader Aung San Suu Kyi of Burma, where troops killed
thousands last year to crush a peaceful democracy movement, said:
``It's terrible. We deplore it.''
   No official response to the events in China has come from the
ruling military government in Burma nor has the state press covered
the events.
   Japan's Prime Minister Sousuke Uno told reporters he was
``seriously concerned'' and ``praying for the return of calm.''
   Prime Minister Lee Kwan Yew of Singapore said he was ``shocked,
horrified and saddened.''
   A spokesman for the South Korean government said, ``The
stability of China is important for peace and stability on the
Korean peninsula.''
   British publisher Robert Maxwell announced in New York he
suspended publication in Europe of China's official
English-language newspaper, China Daily, saying he wouldn't honor
the joint venture because of revulsion over the Beijing massacre.
   About 250 university students threw tomatoes at the Chinese
Embassy in Mexico City and broke a security camera there in a
protest action.
   An editorial in the government newspaper El Nacional said of the
Beijing slaughter: ``It's clear that the bloodbath was deliberate.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
