<FIRST>r a AM-Stokes-Shoplifting     06-05 0285</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Stokes-Shoplifting,0295</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former Mayor Charged with Shoplifting</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SHAKER HEIGHTS, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Cleveland mayor Carl B.
Stokes, now a municipal judge, was charged Monday with petty theft
by a pet store owner who says he stole a $17.25 bag of dog food.
   It was the second shoplifting allegation in six months involving
Stokes, who has been mentioned as a possible Cleveland mayoral
candidate this year.
   In a statement he read Monday to The Associated Press, he said
he would plead innocent to the charge and request a jury trial.
   The judge also said he would continue his judicial duties
between now and his June 26 arraignment, and request an earlier
arraignment.
   ``However, to avoid any appearances of impropriety, I will refer
all cases alleging petty theft to presiding Judge Charles Flemming
for their disposition,'' he said.
   Stokes is accused by Kim Liedtke, owner of the Pad &amp; Fin pet
store, of stealing 20 pounds of dry dog food Friday.
   Petty theft is a first-degree misdemeanor punishable by as much
as six months in jail and a maximum $1,000 fine.
   On Jan. 4, Stokes acknowledged that he took a $2.39 screwdriver
from a Handy Andy store in Bedford last Dec. 15 without paying for
it.
   Stokes was not charged in that incident. He said he had
absent-mindedly put the screwdriver in his pocket, then argued with
a cashier over the price of other merchandise and forgot he had the
screwdriver. He later paid the store $50 restitution.
   Stokes was mayor of Cleveland from 1967 to 1971, then worked as
a newsman in New York for eight years before returning to Cleveland
to practice law in 1980. He was elected a municipal judge in 1983.
</TEXT>
