<FILEID>AP-NR-06-05-89 2314EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-US-China 4thLd-Writethru a0773 06-05 1065</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-China, 4th Ld-Writethru, a0773,1,000</SECOND>
<HEAD>Chinese Students Demonstrate at Capitol, Joined by Lawmakers</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS 9th graf, ``Elsewhere around,'' to recap action in other
cities, deleting 30th graf 2nd ld: ``In addition,'' outdated by this insert.
10th graf edited for transition.</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Bush Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAWRENCE L. KNUTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Chinese students rallied at the Capitol and
across the street from the White House on Monday, chanting, singing
and listening to speeches appealing for international help to
``stop the killing'' in Beijing.
   Members of Congress applauded President Bush's decision to
suspend military sales to China and to cut off contacts with
Chinese military leaders.
   But a few said the United States should go further, ending all
U.S. trade with China and stopping U.S. investment in China's
economy.
   Rep. Thomas S. Foley, D-Wash., the House majority leader
expected to be elected speaker on Tuesday, said after a meeting
with Bush that ``in the very uncertain circumstances at the present
time I think the president is correct in leaving our ambassador in
Beijing.''
   ``It's important both for the flow of information and ... for
strong action to ensure the protection of American citizens as well
as expressing at the highest level our deep concern, our anguish
over further loss of life,'' Foley said.
   House Republican Leader Bob Michel of Illinois called Bush's
decision to stop arms sales ``a measured and, in my view,
appropriate response.''
   In Portland, Ore., former President Reagan said he supported
Bush's criticism of the Chinese government.
   The demonstrating students, from universities and colleges along
the East Coast, held banners and placards aloft in the steamy heat
at the Capitol's West Front displaying slogans that have echoed in
American revolutionary and civil rights history: ``Don't Tread On
Me!'' _ ``Live Free Or Die!'' _ ``We Shall Overcome.''
   Elsewhere around the country, students and supporters also
demonstrated in Cincinnati, Austin, Texas; Flagstaff and Tucson,
Ariz.; Little Rock and Fayetteville, Ark.; Oxford, Miss.;
Morgantown, W.Va.; Lincoln, Neb.; Birmingham and Huntsville, Ala.;
Stillwater, Okla.; Hanover, N.H.; Worcester, Mass.; Helena, Mont.;
Grand Forks and Fargo, N.D.; and Madison, Wis. Many of the protests
took place at college campuses.
   After marching up Pennsylvania Avenue, the Washington group
gathered in Lafayette Park, across from the White House, to show
support for, as one banner read, ``those brothers killed by
troops.'' Some in the crowd, which was estimated at about 3,000 by
police, carried placards with messages such as ``Democracy for
China Now'' and ``Stop China Deaths.''
   Slogans written on headbands, on banners, on placards, on
T-shirts and on flags reflected fury at the crushing of the
pro-democracy demonstration in Beijing's Tiananmen Square by the
Chinese Army.
   A sampling at the Capitol: ``Glory to the Martyrs'' _ ``Down
With Warlords'' _ ``Our Hearts Are Bleeding For The Students'' _
``Help Us Stop the Massacre'' _ ``Retribution!''
   One sign said: ``President Bush _ Read Our Lips _ Break Ties to
Killer Government.''
   Addressing the students, Sen. Alan Cranston, D-Calif., chairman
of the Senate Foreign Relations Subcommittee on East Asian and
Pacific Affairs, said Bush took ``the exact, appropriate steps. ...
I applaud his statement, I applaud his deeds.''
   ``We should provide our arms only to those who use them for
defense and to advance the cause of liberty and democracy,''
Cranston said. ``Otherwise, what do we stand for?''
   Sen. Jesse Helms, R-N.C., took a harder stand, saying he will
introduce legislation to suspend trade and investment ``if the
atrocities continue.''
   Later, Helms told reporters: ``You cannot deal with rattlesnakes
and you cannot deal with communist governments. They are all
rattlesnakes and they will bite you when the occasion arises.''
   Rep. Jim Leach, R-Iowa, said events in Beijing have called into
question the legitimacy of the existing government.
   ``When the statue of liberty was toppled, when the army turned
against the people, the legitimacy of the government of the
People's Republic of China collapsed,'' Leach said.
   Inside the Capitol, Sen. Sam Nunn, D-Ga., chairman of the Senate
Armed Services Committee, endorsed Bush's suspension of U.S.
military sales adding, ``We will need to watch developments closely
to determine what additional measures are necessary.''
   Sen. Christopher Dodd, D-Conn., said Bush's appeals ``could help
to encourage forces of moderation within the (Chinese) army.
   He said the message being sent from Washington is that further
violence ``will profoundly threaten the future relationship between
our two countries.''
   Sen. Richard Lugar, R-Ind., a former chairman of the Foreign
Relations Committee, said: ``No government can long survive at odds
with its own people.''
   ``The events in Tiananmen Square may have sealed the fate of the
current Chinese leadership,'' Lugar said. ``It may take three
months or three years but eventually the students will prevail.''
   The leaders of the Congressional Human Rights Caucus _ Reps.
John Porter, R-Ill., and Tom Lantos, D-Calif. _ issued a statement
urging Bush to recall the U.S. ambassador to China, a step Bush
says would be counterproductive.
   On the House floor, Rep. James Bilbray, D-Nev., urged a national
letter-writing campaign to bombard the Chinese Embassy here with
expressions of ``abhorrence over what happened.''
   Rep. Bill Richardson, D-N.M., said: ``The American honeymoon and
love feast with China that was started in 1971 by Richard Nixon is
over.''
   In Tallahassee, Fla., Rep. Dante Fascell, D-Fla., chairman of
the House Foreign Affairs Committee, said he wants the United
States to meet with other industrialized democratic nations to come
up with a unified response to the situation in China.
   ``It's not only important for the United States to make a strong
moral satement, but that people join together everywhere to protest
this brutality that has existed,'' Fascell said.
   Fascell commented to a group of Chinese students gathered
outside the church where Rep. Claude Pepper's funeral was held.
   Among the demonstrations:
   _About 200 people rallied on the Capitol steps in Austin,
shouting, ``Down with communism'' and ``Power to the people.''
   _About 200 Chinese students marched from the University of
Nebraska in Lincoln to the state Capitol eight blocks away,
carrying effigies of Premier Li Peng and senior leader Deng
Xiaoping and posters calling Li a ``vampire.''
   _About 150 people gathered at the University of Alabama at
Birmingham. Shen-Quan Ho, a student from Tianjin, China, said young
people in China are determined to fight even if it means death.
   ``They are martyrs fighting for freedom, and Chinese all over
the world are proud of them,'' he said.

</TEXT>
</DOC>
