<DOCNO> AP890605-0135 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-05-89 1438EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a e BC-WKD--RecordReviews Adv00   06-05 0510</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-WKD--Record Reviews, Adv 00,0529</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv00</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Anytime</HEAD>
<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>In the Groove: Record Reviews</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARC RICE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   
   ``Love Season'' (Orpheus) _ Alex Bugnon
   
   The first cut on ``Love Season,'' keyboardist Alex Bugnon's
debut album, is fantastic _ a playful, strutting number that jumps
out from the speakers with a shout of joy.
   That the rest of the album fails to live up to ``Going Out,'' is
less the fault of the material than the high standard set by the
lead song. The seven other songs on ``Love Season'' are pretty
good, too.
   ``Going Out'' should be required listening for anyone who thinks
_ maybe with good reason _ that most jazz fusion music is too
sterile and mechanical, music for admiring rather than enjoying.
   Bugnon brings a lot of humanity and feeling to his music, and
avoids allowing his varied influences (his background includes
classical, jazz, gospel and rock) to meld into faceless mush. As
they say, this guy's got personality.
   The album shifts effortlessly from elegant to all-out jams, with
high points including a sharp version of the Brenda Russell hit,
``Piano in the Dark,'' the funky ``Falling for You'' and ``Magie
Noire,'' a percussion and synthesizer party.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   
   ``Conviction'' (Blue Wave) _ Hamell on Trial
   
   Ed Hamell has a chip on his shoulder and a gift for melody, two
things that ought to add up to great rock 'n' roll. What he lacks,
and what sinks his group Hamell on Trial's debut album, is a sense
of humor.
   With a tight four-piece band led by Hamell's brilliant acoustic
guitar playing, ``Conviction'' attacks such things as liars, drugs
and MTV and muses on the pain of love at 100 words per minute. The
album also sets what must be some sort of record by having two
songs containing references to boxer Mike Tyson.
   But after opening with the bright pop of ``Looking for You,''
Hamell on Trial overdoes it with the heaviness. And it's not just
the lyrics. The performances, which include talking blues and
straight-out rock with folk overtones, have a veins-in-the-neck
intensity.
   Listen to some of the great angry artists of rock _ Lennon,
Dylan, Costello, for example _ and you'll get the seriousness
balanced with some humor and compassion. That mix is part of what
made the songs work, but it's an approach that has not been grasped
here.
   Even when Hamell's pledging his love, things get a bit
overwrought. In ``When You're Alone,'' he sings: ``If I were
Michael Tyson standing in the ring, knowing that I needn't fear
another living thing, I'd be standing there, shiny, black and
proud, I'd see you in the audience, I'd lift you from the crowd, if
you needed it, some night when you're alone.''
   Lighten up, Ed.
   The power displayed on ``Conviction'' indicates Hammell on Trial
has what it takes to make a good record. We'll have to tune in next
time to see if they actually do it.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Release Anytime</NOTE>
</DOC>
