<FIRST>a e BC-WKD--Wright Adv16-18   06-05 0905</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-WKD--Wright, Adv 16-18,0941</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv16</HEAD>
<HEAD>$Adv17</HEAD>
<HEAD>$Adv18</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Weekend Editions, June 16-18 and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>Star Watch: Looking for Ms. Wright</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HILLEL ITALIE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Remember William Hurt's sister in ``The
Accidental Tourist,'' the one who marries his boss?
   Or Amy Irving's friend in ``Crossing Delancey,'' the one who has
the baby?
   What about Holly Hunter's fellow beauty contestant in ``Miss
Firecracker,'' the one whose piano recital is ruined by Tim Robbins?
   Picture an actress with big brown eyes, strawberry blond hair,
and a wide smile, specializing in offbeat characters. She has
appeared in John Huston's ``Wise Blood'' and Woody Allen's
``Stardust Memories,'' as well as ``Breaking Away,'' ``The Deer
Hunter'' and ``The Amityville Horror.''
   Her name is Amy Wright and her experiences on film sets are not
of 18-hour days or endless retakes, but of finding ways to fill
free time.
   She can relate well to the character in the long-running
off-Broadway play, ``The Fantasticks'' who pronounces, ``There are
no small actors, only small parts.''
   ``On `Accidental Tourist,' we had two weeks of rehearsal and
that was wonderful,'' the actress recalled. ``Then we started
shooting and I just sat around. I wasn't needed except here and
there, that's the way it goes.
   ``I wanted to be at work; I didn't want to be sitting in a hotel
reading. I got a lot of reading done, but I thought, `What am I
doing? My life is passing me by and I'm just sitting here.' At
least in a play, you're busy all the time.''
   For ``Crossing Delancey,'' she had to make due with a limited
role.
   ``I didn't do a whole biography of where she was born and how
she got to that point in her life,'' Wright said of her character.
``You have a little baby in your arms, you go to a bris, you have
your friends. You can just imagine all that, some things you can
just easily identify with.''
   But Wright's career is picking up. Critics praised her
performance in ``The Accidental Tourist,'' and the actress could
gain wider recognition this fall when she appears opposite Jeff
Daniels in ``Love Hurts.''
   ``I think that more people know who I am,'' Wright said of her
recent string of hit films. ``Now they can connect the name and the
face. I have a good reputation.''
   Her decision to become an actress was a bit of an accident
itself. Wright, a native of Chicago, grew up in a house without a
TV set and had little interest in film or stage. But as a senior in
high school, she became ``inspired.''
   ``I had a mad crush on this fellow at the University of Chicago.
He was an actor, an undergraduate student. He had a friend who was
making 16 mm movies, and I used to hang around.
   ``We went to this acting workshop and the teacher told me I was
really good. She said, `Why don't you try out for plays at your
school or come here and try out.'''
   The crush eventually faded, but she caught the acting bug and
appeared in several high school plays. After majoring in theater
arts at Beloit College, Wright moved to Stockbridge, Mass., and
taught high school.
   ``It served its purpose,'' she said. ``It was a step into the
real world; it was halfway there. I was always able to do summer
stock and get a pretty good workout. Then I went to Rockville,
Ill., where a friend of mine had started The New American Theatre,
which is still going strong.''
   Wright moved to New York in 1974 and appeared on Broadway in
Lanford Wilson's ``5th of July.'' She also became friends with
director Martha Coolidge and made her film debut in Coolidge's
documentary feature, ``Not a Pretty Picture.''
   Parts in ``Girlfriends,'' ``Breaking Away'' and ``The Deer
Hunter'' quickly followed. In 1980, she had a featured role in
``Wise Blood,'' playing the sly Sabbath Lily Hawks in Huston's
adaptation of the Flannery O'Connor story. Wright considers the
film her favorite and enjoyed working with the director.
   ``It was very nice,'' she said. ``We'd start about 8 in the
morning and finish about 4 or 5 in the afternoon. If you got him
telling stories, that was the best. He believed that if you cast
the right person, 90 percent of his job was done as far as the
performance was concerned. He didn't like to tell actors what to
do.''
   But ``Wise Blood'' was a box-office failure and for the next
five years, Wright worked exclusively in theater.
   ``There have been some hard times when I was wondering what
should I do instead with my life. Something more fulfilling than
waiting around for the phone to ring.''
   She appeared on Broadway in Michael Frayn's ``Noises Off,'' and
made a valuable contact with Joan Micklin Silver, who directed
``Crossing Delancey.''
   ``It gave me a boost to get that job,'' Wright said. ``It'd been
a long time; it gave me confidence. Then reading for (director)
Larry Kasden and `Accidental Tourist,' I thought, `Oh, this is
great.'''
   She has finally dropped the dreaded status of ``between parts.''
   ``Things are better,'' said Wright. ``You have to make the
poeple think you're really sought after or they think, `Well, she's
not getting offers so I'm not going to offer anything either.'''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Weekend Editions, June 16-18</NOTE>
