<FILEID>AP-NR-06-05-89 1109EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-Italy-AT&amp;T     06-05 0368</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Italy-AT&amp;T,0383</SECOND>
<HEAD>Italtel, AT&amp;T Sign Major Cooperation Agreement</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY BETH SHERIDAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Italian telecommunications equipment maker
Italtel on Monday signed an agreement with American Telephone &amp;
Telegraph Co. for a far-reaching partnership in manufacturing and
sales of equipment.
   Under the accord, AT&amp;T will acquire 20 percent of Italtel. In
exchange, Italtel's parent, the Italian state holding company STET,
will take a 20 percent share of AT&amp;T-Network Systems International
(ATT-NSI), a joint venture between AT&amp;T and NV Philips of the
Netherlands.
   In addition, AT&amp;T has agreed to make a direct investment of
almost $150 million in Italtel, said an official involved in the
deal who requested anonymity.
   The accord, which was widely expected, was an important victory
for AT&amp;T. It allows the U.S. giant access to the ripe Italian
telecommunications market, which is dominated by Italtel, and
improves AT&amp;T's position for the post-1992 unified European market.
   Stet and Italtel hope to gain advanced technology, investment
and increased credibility through the alliance.
   Both AT&amp;T and Italtel have only limited access to foreign
markets at present.
   Although the value of the share swap wasn't disclosed at a news
conference announcing the deal, AT&amp;T Chairman Robert E. Allen said
they ``balanced out in terms of value.''
   The cooperation agreement was signed following four months of
detailed negotiations between AT&amp;T and Stet-Italtel.
   AT&amp;T was selected as Italtel's partner over Siemens AG of West
Germany, Alcatel NV of France and Sweden's Telefon AB L.M. Ericsson
after a politically charged decision-making process that took more
than a year.
   Allen said it was ``premature'' to estimate the value of the
orders AT&amp;T expected to receive through the partnership.
   But AT&amp;T is expected to win a big chunk of the nearly $26
billion in orders for equipment and technology that the Italian
phone company SIP has planned as part of a five-year investment
plan.
   The AT&amp;T-Italtel agreement involves cooperation in research and
development, production, the purchase of components, sales,
installation and servicing in the fields of public switching,
transmission, support systems and private telecommunications.
   Part of the accord provides for establishment of an
equally-owned company to market a ``common catalogue'' of
AT&amp;T-Italtel telecommunications equipment to European and Asian
markets.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
