<SECOND>PM-Board of Trade, Open,0283</SECOND>
<HEAD>Grain, Soybean Futures Mixed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybeans futures prices turned mixed
after opening lower today on the Chicago Board of Trade.
   Pressure came early on two fronts, the first being the plentiful
rain over the weekend in key growing areas for beans and corn. The
second reason was that the Chinese, thought to be in the market for
as much as a million tons of grain, would be postponing their buy.
   Political upheaval was generally regarded as the cause for the
Chinese decision not to come to the market at this time.
   Both the grains and beans, however, made a comeback within the
first hour and turned mixed as new crop months gained at the
expense of old crop months.
   On the open, wheat was 3 cents to 5{ cents lower, with the
contract for delivery in July at $3.86{ a bushel; corn was \ cent
lower to 1} cents lower, with July $2.60{ a bushel; oats were }
cents higher to 1} cents higher, with July at $1.71 a bushel; and
soybeans 1 were cent lower to 4\ cents lower, with July at $7.02\ a
bushel.
   Livestock and pork futures were mostly higher at the Chicago
Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle were unchanged to .40 cent higher, with June at
68.60 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .50 cent to 93 cent higher,
with August at 78.45 cents a pound; live hogs were .07 cent lower
to .40 cent higher, with June at 48.25 cents a pound; and frozen
pork bellies were .65 cent to 1.25 cents higher, with July at 31.55
cents a pound.
</TEXT>
