<FILEID>AP-NR-06-05-89 1157EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-FishSafety 1stLd-Writethru f0008 06-05 0616</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Fish Safety, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0008,0637</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eds: New throughout with today's testimony. Also moved on general
news wires</HEAD>
<HEAD>Stands for PM-Farm Scene</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DIANE DUSTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A fish industry spokesman said today ``it's
ludicrous'' to claim deficiencies in seafood inspection make eating
seafood more dangerous than eating fat.
   But Lee Weddig, executive vice president of the National
Fisheries Institute, said he favors improved seafood inspection as
much as do consumer groups who made the claim.
   When American try to improve their eating habits by cutting down
on fat they often turn to fish.
   ``Unless legislation establishing a comprehensive mandatory
seafood inspection program is enacted and signed in this Congress,
those same health-conscious consumers will be putting themselves at
increasing risk for serious illness, even death,'' said Ellen Haas,
spokeswoman for the consumer group Public Voice.
   Currently, the Food and Drug Administration has a shellfish
sanitation program and a canned salmon control program, which are
both voluntary, Haas said.
   The National Marine Fisheries Service, in the Department of
Commerce, has a voluntary inspection and grading program, but it
emphasizes uniformity of size, flavor and freedom from blemishes.
It is not a public health program, she said.
   Weddig and Haas were among the witnesses who testified today
before the House Energy and Commerce subcommittee on oversight and
investigations, which is gathering information for possible fish
inspection legislation.
   While the Agriculture Department is in charge of most food
inspection, including livestock and poultry, it does not inspect
seafood, Haas said. In an interview Friday, she said it would make
sense to put such an inspection under the USDA because it already
has the structure.
   Weddig said he also favors USDA inspection of seafood.
   He said his organization went to Congress in 1985 seeking an
inspection program. He said the National Marine Fisheries Service
has been working for two years on the best approach and will be
making recommendations to Congress.
   ``These hearings are running parallel to that,'' said Weddig.
``We hope they will come together.''
   But Weddig said ``it's ludicrous'' to make a claim such as that
made by Public Voice. He said the fish sold commercially is safe.
   ``Waters that are polluted, mostly in the inland lakes, have
been closed to commercial fishing for years,'' he said.
   As for the salmon affected by the oil spill in Alaska, Weddig
said public officials were monitoring the catch carefully and would
not allow anything to be sold that was not safe.
   The subcommittee hearing, chaired by Rep. John Dingell, D-Mich.,
was the first congressional hearing on seafood since 1974.
   Haas said it came at a critical time.
   ``Annual consumption of seafood in the United States increased
by over 20 percent between 1980 and 1987 and is now well over 3
billion pounds,'' she said.
   Haas said seafood has certain characteristics that increase
health risks. Namely, it comes from uncontrolled environments where
bacteria and parasites dwell.
   ``The waters from which fish are taken may be polluted with
sewage, industrial chemicals or pesticides,'' she said. ``In
addition, certain types of seafood, such as shellfish, actually
concentrate contaminants in their tissue.''
   Though cooking kills many causes of food poisoning, fish often
is eaten raw.
   Haas said that according to the federal Centers for Disease
Control statistics from 1973 to 1984, more people got sick from
fish and shellfish than from beef and poultry combined.
   She said the figures attain added significance when it's
realized that Americans eat more than four times as much beef and
three times as much poultry as they do of seafood.
   Public Voice has been working with Dingell's subcommittee on the
issue. Dingell said in March he hoped to have legislation prepared
soon.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890605-0154 </DOCNO>
