<FIRST>u f PM-OilSpill 1stLd-Writethru f0028 06-05 0397</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Oil Spill, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0028,0406</SECOND>
<HEAD>EPA Says Oil Spill in Northwestern Colorado Contained</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 6th graf, `Calls to...', with 3 grafs to UPDATE with Amoco
comment. Picks up 7th graf, `The Yampa...'; Also moved on general news
wires</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CRAIG, Colo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 13,000-gallon oil spill that fouled the
Yampa River in northwestern Colorado has been contained, said an
environmental official who criticized the weekend cleanup effort by
the oil company.
   The spill occurred Friday, when a pipeline carrying light crude
oil running beneath the river burst. Amoco Pipeline Co. shut off
the line after Craig police reported the pipe break.
   Amoco crews tried to contain the spill Saturday but weren't
successful until Sunday.
   ``They didn't really put up the booms correctly, which was a
factor in causing the (oil trap anchor) cable to snap,'' said Jeff
Knoy, a spokesman in Denver for the Environmental Protection
Agency. ``They haven't had a lot of experience, or they put it up
incorrectly.
   ``Basically, Amoco's not done the best job. And we've had to
jump on them some,'' he said. ``Part of the problem was high water.
I don't think they've had to do this in a while, but they didn't do
a very good job.''
   But Amoco spokesman Jack Rigg said today the company ``did
everything we reasonably could.''
   He said the pipeline was shut off within 45 minutes of the time
the leak was reported, and said Amoco had 40 people and several
thousand feet of booms at the river within two hours. But the
river's roughness and remoteness foiled those early cleanup
efforts, he said.
   Rigg said Amoco managed to get the oil contained and diverted
within 50 miles of the spill by Sunday, and crews with shovels and
plastic buckets were cleaning up the 50-mile stretch today.
   The Yampa River is a breeding ground for three endangered
species of fish: humpback and bonytail chubs and Colorado squawfish.
   ``The environmental impact was minimal, considering what it
would have been,'' Knoy said Sunday. ``The Fish and Wildlife
Service went up and down the river quite a bit the last few days.
As of last night, there were no dead fish, no fish in distress and
no dead birds.''
   The spill was not expected affect drinking water in this town of
8,000 because it occurred downstream of the point where water is
taken from the river.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890605-0158 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-05-89 1338EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-ConsumerSurvey     06-05 0274</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Consumer Survey,0282</SECOND>
<HEAD>Survey: Consumer Confidence Still Strong</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Embargoed for release 6:30 p.m. EDT; time set by source</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   American consumers' assessment of current
economic conditions is down but expectations remain positive about
the next six months, according to a survey released Monday.
   More than 20 percent of 5,000 households nationwide surveyed in
May by the Conference Board said they anticipate that business
conditions will improve in the next six months. That was up from 17
percent a month earlier.
   Thirty percent of those surveyed said they believe current
business conditions are ``good,'' a slight rise from the April
survey. Despite an increase in unemployment, 34.5 percent of
respondents said they believe jobs are ``plentiful,'' the same as
in April.
   The number of people expecting more jobs to become available
increased to 19 percent from 15.4 percent, but there was also an
increase in the number of people who expect the reverse to happen,
to 15 percent from 13 percent.
   ``The fact that consumer confidence has remained strong, despite
signs of a slowing economy, is reassuring,'' Fabian Linden,
executive director of the board's Consumer Research Center, said in
a statement.
   ``Consumers, who are evidently in the first instance wage
earners, have always been quick to sense oncoming recession,'' he
said. ``But there are none of the indications in recent survey
readings that generally signal troubles ahead.''
   The board's monthly consumer confidence index gained one point
to 117.8, with 1985 as 100. That was down from 120.2 a year ago.
   The Conference Board is a nonprofit business network that
provides information and management and economic research for
business leaders worldwide.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890605-0159 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-05-89 1332EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f BC-Britain-Stocks 1stLd-Writethru   06-05 0221</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Britain-Stocks, 1st Ld-Writethru,0227</SECOND>
<HEAD>London Shares End Lower</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: UPDATES with closing prices</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Share prices on London's stock exchange ended
significantly lower Monday for the fifth session in a row, as the
market remained unsettled by weakness in sterling and the outlook
for British interest rates.
   Trading activity was dull, however, as many players stuck to the
sidelines, waiting for further evidence of Britain's economic
performance.
   The Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-share index closed 14.1
points lower at 2,088.5, just 0.6 point below its best level
reached at mid-afternoon. At its lowest, the index was down 26.1
points in morning business.
   Volume slowed sharply to 359.2 million shares from 635.9 million
shares on Friday.
   The major factor worrying the London market was the weakness in
sterling, which continued to lose ground despite reported
intervention by the Bank of England to bolster the currency.
   Players were concerned the pound's weakness could trigger yet
another rise in interest rates, which were pushed up 1 percentage
point to 14 percent last month.
   ``There's been no real underpinning of sterling'' from the 14
percent interest rates, said Bill Smith, a market analyst at
Prudential Bache Securities in London. ``The danger of 15 percent
is that much higher, so the danger of a hard landing (for the
British economy) is that much higher.''
</TEXT>
