<FILEID>AP-NR-06-05-89 2132EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a f AM-BusinessMirror Adv07   06-05 0548</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Business Mirror, Adv 07,0567</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv07</HEAD>
<HEAD>For release AMs Wednesday, June 7</HEAD>
<HEAD>The Consumer As Forecaster</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN CUNNIFF</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Analyst</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The latest consumer survey report suggests that
economic expansion will slow, unemployment and interest rates might
rise and inflation will dig in at a rate of at least 5 percent.
   This isn't an especially negative forecast, because the economy
is expected to continue expanding, but it is a downturn. Consumers
remain comfortable, according to one interpreter, but they expect
things to get worse.
   That information, from the University of Michigan's Survey
Research Center, is being distributed to clients and is destined to
become part of the Commerce Department's index of leading economic
indicators.
   As part of that index, it then will be used by investors,
economists, bankers, regulators, business people and others who
seek to get a peak into the future and, if possible, take some
action about events to come.
   But can consumers forecast?
   You bet they can, says Richard T. Curtin, director of the
Michigan institute. They can, that is, if they are questioned
professionally and their responses recorded and analyzed
scientifically.
   To demonstrate their accuracy, Curtin measured expectations with
what followed in several areas, including interest rates, jobless
rates and inflation rates _ and found a remarkable accuracy rate.
   He found, for instance, that consumers anticipated changes in
interest rates two quarters, or six months, in advance of changes
in the prime interest rate. That beats many a professional's record.
   For unemployment, Curtin found their anticipation time span even
longer, at three quarters or nine months in advance. Regarding
inflation, the foresight was only one quarter in advance but the
accuracy rating was especially high.
   The same general levels of accuracy also pertain to some of the
more specific money items that are measured. Changes in consumer
expectations, for example, accurately foretell housing and vehicle
markets six months in advance.
   There is little mystery to why consumers, en masse, can
forecast. To some extent, in sales for example, they are not
forecasting so much as foretelling. They are, that is, telling the
markets what they intend to do.
   Measured accurately, their own economic condition becomes a
projection of the whole economy, of which consumers are the biggest
segment, bigger than business or government.
   In each area of the Michigan survey, consumers are asked to give
their overall opinions and to describe in their own words reasons
for holding these views. Of course, their financial condition and
hopes enter the picture.
   According to Curtin, when many people change from an optimistic
to a pessimistic view at the same time, it has been found that a
widespread shift toward postponement of expenditures follows.
   It is in this manner, he says, that the economic optimism and
confidence of individual families exert their influence on the
course of the aggregate economy.
   Of particular interest in the latest monthly survey, based on
500 interviews in which about 25 core questions were asked, is the
attitude toward inflation and interest rates.
   Many professional forecasters in financial and economic circles
are expecting a decline in interest rates, reasoning that the
latest economic measurements show the inflation threat is ebbing.
   Consumers, however, see worsening inflation and higher interest
rates.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Advance for AMs Wednesday, June 7.</NOTE>
</DOC>
