<HEAD>Dollar Mostly Higher</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: AMs planned by 5:30 p.m. EDT</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar ended mostly higher in Europe on Monday
after uneven trading that reflected mixed signals the market was
receiving on the dollar's short-term direction.
   Gold prices also rose.
   Concern about the violence in China heightened the dollar's role
as a ``safe-haven'' currency, dealers said. At the same time, a cut
in the U.S. prime rate to 11 percent from 11.5 percent by major
U.S. banks was a bearish factor, they said.
   ``There are too many signals in the market and therefore no
clear direction,'' said Shani Shamah, corporate dealer at
Continental Illinois Ltd. in London.
   The market's unsettled tone kept many corporate players on the
sidelines, which resulted in thin volume, dealers said.
   In London, the dollar gained against the British pound. It cost
$1.5815 to buy one pound, cheaper than $$1.5900 late Friday.
   Other late dollar rates in Europe, compared with late Friday:
1.9630 West German marks, up from 1.9585; 1.6950 Swiss francs, up
from 1.6850; 6.6645 French francs, up from 6.6470; 2.2010 Dutch
guilders, down from 2.2180; 1,416.50 Italian lire, down from
1,428.50; 1.2003 Canadian dollars, down from 1.2063.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day
begins, the dollar fell 1.15 yen to a closing 140.65 yen. Later, in
London, it was quoted at 141.75 yen.
   Gold rose in London to a late bid price of $366.25 a troy ounce,
compared with late Friday's $$362.25.
   In Zurich, gold rose to close at a bid $366.00 compared with
$362.00 late Friday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold rose $2.55 to close at a bid $369.20.
   Silver bullion prices rose on the London market where the metal
was trading at a late bid price of $5.31 a troy ounce, compared
with Friday's 5.21.
