<FIRST>r f AM-Scotus-Banking     06-05 0377</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Scotus-Banking,0393</SECOND>
<HEAD>Supreme Court to Review Illinois-Florida Bank Dispute</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD CARELLI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court on Monday agreed to decide
whether Florida may block an Illinois-based bank holding company
from establishing an industrial savings bank in Miami.
   The justices said they will review the dispute even though Bush
administration lawyers, asked for their views, said a change in
federal banking law may have made the case moot.
   Continental Bank Corporation, based in Illinois, filed an
application with the Florida Department of Banking an Finance in
1981 to establish and run an industrial savings bank in Miami.
   The proposed bank would not accept demand deposits or make
commercial loans _ making it a so-called ``non-bank bank'' that
fell outside the federal law's definition of banks.
   But deposits in the proposed bank would be insured by the
Federal Deposit Insurance Corporation.
   The application was denied, and Continental subsequently sued in
federal court. The suit alleged that Florida's denial of the
application was unconstitutional.
   Under federal banking law, a bank holding company based in one
state may not establish a bank in another state unless the latter
state's laws specifically authorize it to do so.
   But because ``non-bank banks'' fall outside the scope of federal
banking law, state regulation of such institutions is subject to
the Constitution's requirement that states not unduly interfere
with or discriminate against interstate commerce.
   While the Continental case was pending before a federal appeals
court in 1987, federal banking law was amended to include in the
definition of ``bank'' any institution the deposits of which are
insured by the FDIC.
   Because the proposed industrial savings bank in Miami was to be
FDIC-insured, it fell within the scope of federal banking law and
subject to Florida's legally authorized discrimination.
   The 11th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals, however, refused to
declare the case moot.
   It instead ruled that the Florida law banning the industrial
savings bank was unconstitutional. The appeals court said it could
say that the change in federal law would make Continental's
operation of the Florida institution ``banking'' activity ``in
every instance.''
   Gerald A. Lewis, who heads the state Department of Banking and
Finance, then sought Supreme Court review.
   The case is Lewis vs. Continental Bank Corp., 87-1955.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890605-0165 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-05-89 1424EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Spain-Bankers     06-05 0452</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Spain-Bankers,0472</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bankers Skeptical Of Brady Plan</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FRANCISCO CONDE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MADRID, Spain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. Treasury Secretary Nicholas Brady
called on international bankers Monday to help impove Third World
economies by forgiving some of their outstanding debt.
   Brady told the International Monetary Conference, whose
membership includes 99 major commercial banks in 22 countries, that
bankers could enhance their claims if they offered countries the
types of debt reductions proposed in the so-called Brady Plan.
   The plan stresses cutting debt principal and interest payments
over continued lending to heavily indebted countries.
   ``I ask you to compare the risks of inaction with the benefits
of concluding transactions that meet the tests of realism and
reasonableness,'' Brady said.
   If banks follow the Brady plan, ``bank claims will be somewhat
lower, but they will be better claims _ and they will be better
serviced,'' he said.
   But Brady added that Third World debtor nations, which owe about
half their $1.2 trillion debt to commercial banks, would only be
eligible for the plan if they reformed their troubled economies.
   Some bankers, however, were skeptical of the propposal.
   ``It's a bit one-sided to state that debt reduction by the
commercial banks is the answer to the problem,'' Fop Hoogendijk,
managing director of the Amsterdam-Rotterdam Bank NV, told
reporters. ``People should pay their interest.''
   The two main international lending agencies, the International
Monetary Fund and the World Bank, have backed the debt reduction
strategy, known as the Brady plan, as have the major industrialized
creditor nations.
   In other developments at Monday's conference, bankers and
industrialists discussed the European Economic Community's plan to
drop internal trade and capital barriers in 1992.
   Helmut Sihler, the chief executive officer of the West German
chemical company Henkel KGAA, said companies based outside the EEC
will reap early benefits from the plan. But he said EEC-based
companies face more obstacles to taking advantage of the single
market because they are oriented toward their own national markets.
   Percy Barnevik, the head of Swiss engineering firm ABB Asea
Brown Boveri Ltd., said two-thirds of the EEC-based companies would
be hurt as a result of the market integration proposed in the
Single European Act.
   Barnevik said politicians stressed the positive aspects of
economic unification but ignored the ``hardships ... reduction of
plants, reduction of people'' inherent to industrial progress.
   Other IMC panelists underlined their belief that EEC companies
faced their principal challenge from ever-stronger Japanese and
American companies, regardless of the creation of the single market.
   ``It's not a question of Europe `92. The problem is the
cutthroat outside competition,'' Jean-Louis Beffa, the chief
executive officer of the French glassmaker Saint Gobain, said.
   ``Europe 1992 is not a problem _ it's an answer.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
