<FILEID>AP-NR-06-05-89 1526EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Scotus-Milken     06-05 0478</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Scotus-Milken,0495</SECOND>
<HEAD>Court Clears Way for Drexel Settlement</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court on Monday cleared the way
for Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc. plead guilty to six felonies and
pay $650 million in a long-delayed settlement of a landmark
securities fraud case.
   The court, without comment, rejected an appeal by Drexel junk
bond financier Michael Milken to have the federal judge presiding
over the case disqualified on grounds of a conflict of interest.
   Milken, his brother Lowell and a former colleague, Pamela
Monzert, sought to have U.S. District Judge Milton Pollack in
Manhattan removed from their case.
   Pollack must approve a settlement announced in May between the
New York investment firm and the Securities and Exchange
Commission. The settlement resolves charges including insider
trading in more than 20 alleged fraud schemes.
   Approval of that settlement is a precondition for Drexel to
plead guilty to six felony counts and pay a record $650 million in
fines and restitution in a separate criminal settlement with the
Justice Department.
   Martin Flumenbaum, an attorney for Michael Milken, declined to
discuss the Supreme Court ruling.
   The Milkens had argued that Pollack has an apparent conflict of
interest because his wife is receiving $30 million from the sale of
a corporation in which Drexel helped set up the financing.
   The acquisition of the corporation owned by Mrs. Pollack is
unrelated to the financial dealings that landed Drexel and Milken
in trouble with the government.
   Pollack refused to disqualify himself from the Drexel-Milken
cases and the 2nd U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals last year said the
judge acted properly.
   ``We believe...a reasonable person would not conclude that the
judge's impartiality could reasonably be questioned,'' the appeals
court said. ``Judge Pollack's connection (to Drexel) is too remote
to mandate recusal because Drexel has no obligation direct or
indirect to Mrs. Pollack.''
   The challenge to the judge's role in the case has held up
resolution of the SEC's lawsuit against Drexel, which was filed
last September. The SEC also named Milken in the civil suit and
Monday's Supreme Court ruling clears the way for a civil fraud
trial of Milken.
   The 2nd Circuit court refused to assign the case to a different
judge, but barred Pollack from approving the settlement until the
Supreme Court acted on Milken's appeal.
   Once settlement of the SEC's civil suit against Drexel is
concluded, Drexel formally will plead guilty to the felonies and
pay $300 million to the government and $350 million for
compensation of investors victimized by alleged insider trading.
   Drexel originally tried to get Pollack to disqualify himself
from the SEC suit but later dropped its objections.
   The ruling does not affect a separate 98-count criminal fraud
and racketeering indictment against Michael and Lowell Milken that
contains charges similar to ones filed by the SEC. A trial in New
York in that case is scheduled for March 1990.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890605-0169 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-05-89 1527EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f BC-AutoSales     06-05 0421</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Auto Sales,0435</SECOND>
<HEAD>Big Three Report May Sales</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: AMs planned</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-Auto Sales-Table</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDERICK STANDISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The nation's Big Three automakers said Monday
that late May car and light truck sales fell 5.6 percent from last
year, ending the two-month spring buying season that saw a flurry
of incentives to spark sales.
   General Motors Corp., Ford Motor Co. and Chrysler Corp. said
they sold vehicles at a daily rate of 47,359 during from May 21-31,
compared with a daily rate of 50,181 in the same 1988 period.
   Car sales were down 4.2 percent and truck sales were off 7.9
percent.
   The 10-day period last year was one of the strongest of 1988,
which proved to be the second-best sales year in automobile history.
   Through the first five months of this year, the car- and
truck-selling pace is lagging 5.3 percent behind the rate last
year, with cars running 7.4 percent behind last year's rate and
trucks off by 1.6 percent.
   Typically, April and May are among the hottest selling times in
the automobile industry, as Americans prepare for summer vacations
and weekend road trips.
   Sales through March of this year ran below expectations,
resulting in larger-than-anticipated inventories. The Big Three
offered incentive packages in early April that boosted cash
rebates, lowered finance rates and extended the deal to more models.
   The strategy appears to have worked somewhat.
   Combined April and May car and truck sales by the Big Three
automakers ran 0.7 percent ahead of vehicle sales during those two
months last year. This year's daily sales rate was 38,944 vehicles
in April and May, compared with a rate of 38,654 last year.
   But inventories remained swollen, and companies have been
temporarily idling plants to reduce them. Speculation has continued
that summer shutdowns, during which factories are retooled for next
year's models, may be longer than normal.
   Ford sustained the largest decline in car sales among the Big
Three in late May. Its cars sold at daily rate of 9,121 during,
down 8.4 percent from 9,956 last year. Light trucks made by Ford
sold at a rate 2 percent below last year.
   GM said late-May car sales were 16,400 a day this year, down 3.1
percent from the 16,927 rate during the period last year. Light
truck sales during the period fell 16.5 percent.
   Chrysler posted a modest 0.7 percent gain in car sales with a
daily rate of 4,439, compared with 4,407 last year. Chrysler's
late-May truck sales were up 0.3 percent.
</TEXT>
