<FIRST>u f AM-Northwest     06-05 0423</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Northwest,0437</SECOND>
<HEAD>NWA Rejects All Bids; Invites Revisions</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Lead planned with further details.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TONY KENNEDY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   NWA Inc.'s board of directors rejected all
offers to buy the company Monday and invited suitors to revise
their bids, but the parent of Northwest Airlines indicated there
was no assurance it would get an offer it deemed acceptable.
   ``NWA Inc. has received a number of acquisition proposals in
response to its request for offers,'' the board said in a
statement. ``None of the proposals is acceptable in its present
form. Further, none of the proposals is sufficiently more
attractive than the others.''
   The statement said each of the bids is ``subject to unacceptable
material conditions,'' but did not elaborate. However, in letters
to bidders the company said interested buyers needed to address
concerns raised by federal regulators and the issue of compensating
NWA in the event it accepted an offer that later collapsed.
   NWA stock tumbled $2 to $106.75 a share in late trading on the
New York Stock Exchange following the company's announcement.
   The company declined to identify bidders who met last week's
deadline for submitting offers or to outline the proposals.
   Known bidders included oil billionaire Marvin Davis, who earlier
this year made a $2.7 billion buyout proposal; New York-based Pan
Am Corp., which has made a proposal valued at $3.3 billion;
Northwest's 20,000-member machinists' union; and an investment
group led by former hotel executive Alfred Checchi which includes
KLM Royal Dutch Airlines and the Australian holding company Elders
IXL Ltd.
   A five-member committee of the NWA board reviewed offers from at
least four groups. The board said Monday that suitors had until
June 16 to submit revisions ``so as to enhance the attractiveness
of their proposals.''
   A letter to the bidders directed them to be specific about their
ability to finalize a deal in light of financing concerns and
scrutiny by the U.S. Department of Transportation, which regulates
the airline industry.
   Accepting a proposal that later might fall through would hurt
NWA, and in revising proposals the bidders should consider means of
compensating NWA for such damage, the letter said.
   ``There can be no assurance that a sale of NWA or any other
transaction will result from NWA's review of alternatives,'' the
letter said.
   Pan Am was the only bidder to disclose details of its financial
package, which could support a bid of $110 a share.
   The takeover firm Kohlberg Kravis Roberts &amp; Co. has been rumored
as a possible bidder but has declined comment.
</TEXT>
