<FILEID>AP-NR-06-05-89 2004EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-StealthCrashes 1stLd-Writethru f0119 06-05 0436</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Stealth Crashes, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0119,0448</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fatigue Suspected in Fatal Stealth Crashes</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: ADDS 2 grafs at end with A-7 jets being transferred. Also moved
on general news wires</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LAS VEGAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pilot fatigue and disorientation may have been
a factor in fatal crashes of two secret Stealth fighters in
California and Nevada, according to heavily censored Air Force
accident reports.
   The 1986 and 1987 crashes involved aircraft stationed at Nellis
Air Force Base north of Las Vegas.
   The reports, released by Nellis, indicate the pilots fought
fatigue brought on by a rigorous flight schedules, with many pilots
working 12- to 14-hour shifts.
   The secret jets flew only at night until Nov. 10, when the Air
Force acknowledged the existence of the radar-eluding jets and said
they would begin daytime operations.
   Fifty-two Stealth fighters are assigned to the 4450th Tactical
Fighter Group at Nellis, with the program operating out of the
Tonopah Test Range, 150 miles northwest of Las Vegas.
   The reports suggest that disorientation resulting from the night
environment or certain aircraft features may have contributed to
the crashes. They did not specify the causes of the crashes but
outlined circumstances surrounding the accidents.
   The first crash occurred July 11, 1986, about 17 miles northeast
of Bakersfield, Calif., killing the pilot. The report indicates
there was no precrash fire or attempt by the pilot to eject and no
indication of mechanical failure.
   In a memo dated the day before the crash, Lt. Col. John Miller,
a squadron commander, wrote: ``I believe that these extended hours
are taking their toll on overall pilot performance. I have detected
more and more instances of poor judgment that weren't evident
two-three months ago.''
   The pilots flew A-7 aircraft for proficiency during the day,
then flew the Stealth flights at night.
   The second crash occurred Oct. 14, 1987, about 61 miles east of
Alamo, also killing the pilot. Again, there was no indication of a
precrash fire or of attempts to eject.
   There are only three known crashes of the Stealth jet. A crash
occurred when Lockheed Corp., the manufacturer, was testing the jet.
   In Washington on Monday, the Air Force announced the A-7 jets
assigned to the 4450th Tactical Group were being transferred to the
Air National Guard. The service said the 18 A-7's would be replaced
with eight AT-38 jets.
   The Air Force declined further comment. But one official who
would not be identified by name said the service could now increase
training in the stealth fighter itself since the end of strict
secrecy made possible daytime flights.
   The stealth fighter carries the military designation F-117A.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890605-0173 </DOCNO>
