<FILEID>AP-NR-06-05-89 2025EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-Hasbro     06-05 0332</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hasbro,0346</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hasbro Adopts Anti-takeover Measures</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PAWTUCKET, R.I. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Toy manufactuer Hasbro Inc. said Monday
it has adopted measures to stave off potentially hostile takeover
bids after rumors the company might become a target.
   The measures do not prohibit sale of the company, but
effectively give shareholders the right to buy Hasbro stock at a
discount in the event of a hostile takeover bid.
   The move follows the hospitalization of Hasbro Chairman Stephen
D. Hassenfeld, 47, for treatment of pneumonia, which has stirred
rumors the company might be sold if he does not return to work.
   Hasbro, which was the second most actively traded company on the
American Stock Exchange last week, closed Monday down 37.5 cents at
$21.25.
   The shareholder rights plan is ``intended to assure that
shareholders receive fair and equal treatment in connection with
any effort to gain control of the company without paying all
shareholders a premium value,'' Hasbro President Alan G. Hassenfeld
said in a statement.
   The plan, approved by the company's board, ``meet the board's
desire to provide protection against abusive takeover tactics such
as partial tender offers and open market purchases,'' he said.
   Under the plan, Hasbro shareholders of record June 15 will get
one preference share for each common share they now hold.
   If a person or group buys or annouces a tender offer to buy 20
percent or more of Hasbro common stock, preference shares will
allow Hasbro stockholders to buy more stock at a low price.
   Hasbro directors may buy back the rights for one cent per share.
The rights expire June 30, 1999.
   The release said the plan contains exceptions for the Hassenfeld
family and related entities, but did not elaborate. The family
controls nearly 30 percent of Hasbro's common stock.
   The company also staggered terms for board of directors, which
helps prevent hostile parties from acquiring control of the board
at once.
   Stephen Hassenfeld was listed in stable condition Monday at
Columbia Presbyterian Medical Center in New York.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
