<FIRST>r f AM-VehicleProblems     06-05 0230</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Vehicle Problems,0239</SECOND>
<HEAD>Report: U.S. Automakers Gaining Ground in Quality</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. automakers have made headway in improving
the quality of their new cars this year but still lag behind
Japanese imports, according to a survey released Monday.
   The survey by J.D. Power and Associates showed the number of
problems reported during the first 90 days of vehicle ownership
fell for domestic and imported makers, indicating the industry was
doing a better job at improving quality.
   According to the survey, owners of domestic cars reported 163
problems per 100 vehicles this year, down from 177 in a similar
survey last year. Owners of Japanese vehicles reported 119 problems
per 100 this year, compared with 144 last year.
   The survey showed the Nissan Maxima had the fewest problems per
100 vehicles sold, with 83. It was followed by the Buick LeSabre
and the Toyota Corolla, both with 89, the Ford Crown Victoria at 91
and the Mercedes-Benz S-class at 93.
   On a nameplate-by-nameplate basis, the Mercedes-Benz had the
fewest problems with 103 per 100 vehicles, followed by Porsche at
106, Nissan at 111, Honda at 112 and Toyota at 117.
   European imports showed the largest number of problems for every
100 vehicles sold, at 204 this year, compared with 258 during the
1988 survey.
   J.D. Power, based in Agoura Hills, Calif., publishes a monthly
report on automotive marketing.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
