<FIRST>r f BC-BusinessHighlights     06-05 0851</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Business Highlights,0890</SECOND>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Economists said major banks' reduction of their
prime interest rates by a half-point to 11 percent did not
necessarily signal a full-scale plunge in interest rates for the
near future.
   Experts said Monday's cut in the prime was more an attempt by
the banks to attract business than an indication they expect the
Federal Reserve to push market rates sharply lower to forestall an
economic recession.
   The prime is a benchmark used to set interest rates on a variety
of bank credit ranging from corporate loans to adjustable home
mortgages.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. sales of cars and light trucks tumbled 3.5
percent in late May, automakers reported, dampening overall results
for the usually robust two-month spring buying season.
   ``The spring selling season was a bust,'' Joseph Phillippi, an
auto analyst with Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc. in New York, said
Monday.
   The eight major U.S. automakers reported they sold vehicles at
an average daily rate of 52,767 during the May 21-31 sales period
this year, compared with a daily rate of 54,654 in the year-earlier
period.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   American businesses said they have yanked
workers from Beijing because of the army's massacre of civilians,
and U.S. airlines canceled China layovers to avoid stranding planes
if airports closed.
   Aside from the shock and horror at the unexpected carnage in
Beijing, the reaction Monday from executives that do business in
China signaled a new uncertainty about the economic impact of the
military's crackdown.
   In Hong Kong, meanwhile, share prices plummeted in nervous
reaction to China's crackdown on pro-democracy demonstrators, and
thousands of residents staged funeral processions for slain
protesters.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A sharply divided Supreme Court erected
significant new barriers for workers who try to prove with
statistical evidence that they are victims of racial bias.
   In another decision Monday, the high court cleared the way for
Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc. to plead guilty to six felonies and pay
$650 million in a long-delayed settlement of a landmark securities
fraud case.
   The court rejected an appeal by Drexel junk bond financier
Michael Milken to have the federal judge presiding over the case
disqualified on grounds of a conflict of interest.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
