<DOCNO> AP890605-0182 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-05-89 2149EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Japan-Markets     06-05 0235</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-Markets,0245</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Jumps, Share Prices Plunge</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar opened sharply higher against the
Japanese yen Tuesday morning, while share prices on the Tokyo Stock
Exchange plunged.
   The dollar started at 142.50 yen, a sharp 1.85-yen gain from
Monday's close of 140.65 yen.
   A trader with the Bank of Tokyo attributed the dollar's higher
opening in Tokyo to its overnight upswing in New York, where
investors bought the currency following a federal reserve bank
selling operation conducted to increase the amount of money in the
market by selling bonds, without manipulating the discount rate.
   ``Investors took the action as indicating the Feds would not
ease the monetary policy by lowering the federal fund rate,
although it was expected, and began buying the dollar,'' the trader
said.
   Japanese investors followed the trend on Wall Street and also
bought the U.S. currency, he said.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues, which shed
210.34 points Monday, quickly lost 209.93 points, or 0.63 percent,
to fall further to 33,255.15 points within the first 15 minutes of
morning trading.
   Dealers said the Nikkei declined after a 37.16-point loss in the
Dow Jones industrial average in New York overnight.
   The yen's decline against the dollar on the foreign exchange and
the deteriorating student-military dispute in China also
discouraged trading, said a dealer with a major securities firm in
Tokyo, speaking on condition of anonymity.
</TEXT>
