<DOCNO> AP890605-0183 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-05-89 2155EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-CaliforniaInsurance     06-05 0337</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-California Insurance,0349</SECOND>
<HEAD>California Insurance Department Begins Rollback Investigation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELISABETH DUNHAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Regulators are sifting through thousands of
financial documents to decide which insurers may be exempt from
rate rollbacks approved by California voters, Insurance
Commissioner Roxani Gillespie said Monday.
   If the 850 boxes filled with exemption applications from
insurers doing business in California are any indication, it could
be some time before policyholders see a change in their insurance
bills.
   ``Our intent is to have them all out of here by November,''
Gillespie said. ``Some people will do what we tell them, others
will appeal and go to court. It will depend upon the extent
litigation ensues from our decision.''
   In May, the state Supreme Court upheld most of Proposition 103 _
the insurance rate-reduction ballot measure approved by voters last
November _ setting the stage for the Insurance Department to decide
how the law is enforced.
   Insurers will be allowed to increase rates without prior state
approval until November. However, any amount that the insurance
commissioner rules to be excessive, when measured against a
standard of a ``fair rate of return,'' will have to be refunded to
customers, with interest.
   Gillespie predicted few insurers will raise their rates during
the next six months.
   She spoke to reporters at a news conference at the new rate
rollback office, where about 35 financial examiners will look at
thousands of documents submitted by insurers. Another 35 examiners
will work at an office in Los Angeles.
   Many companies may have gone overboard in submitting documents
in order to play it safe, turning in dozens of boxes, Gillespie
said.
   Most of the more than 700 insurers doing business in California
have filed for some kind exemption, she said.
   While all types of insurance may be subject to rollbacks under
the new law, much of the attention has focused on auto insurance.
   Under the measure, people with clean driving records will be
entitled to a 20 percent rate discount starting in November.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
